-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PG\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 20\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2008 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 When some 40 chief executives from the Indonesian business circle got together last October, instead of talking about bottom lines and boardroom matters, they were trying to understand environmental sustainability.\par \par \uc2 "There was an enormous amount of enthusiasm at the meeting, as the executives were beginning to understand the concepts of sustainability", says Neil Franklin, sustainability director at Asia-Pacific resources international (April), a pulp and paper company based in Indonesia.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 "Asia is on the development curve, so business leaders are just coming to comprehend the issues, which had not been needed before and they're realising the competitive advantage sustainability can give to their business."\par \par \uc2 The meeting of local CEOs, was hosted by April - the only Indonesian member company of the world business council for sustainable development - in order to spearhead the establishment of a regional chapter in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Though Asia may still be at an early stage, corporate culture is changing as more companies wake up to the reality that \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  has to extend to environmental sustainability.\par \par \uc2 Mark Newton, environmental policy manager for sustainable business at \uc2 Dell\uc2 , which is building its products base in Asia, says he was "pleasantly surprised" to see the company's supply chain customers in the region adhering to greenhouse gas emission standards.\par \par \uc2 "Most of them were surprisingly well-informed and saw the benefits of going green and the return on investment, that it can help them to increase their efficiency and expand their business."\par \par \uc2 In spite of the promising signs, most companies are still not enacting environmental initiatives. Management vision is not aligned with practice.\par \par \uc2 "What's needed is a high level of commitment. Many Asian companies have good intentions with regards to sustainability, but it's not a top priority.\par \par \uc2 "As soon as the economic situation changes or there are other external circumstances, the environmental initiatives drop away", adds Mr Newton.\par \par \uc2 Perhaps part of the reason for the inaction has been because the "go green" mantra has become a fashionable way for corporations to boost their public image.\par \par \uc2 But the real problem seems to stem from the lack of leadership effort at the top management level.\par \par \uc2 A survey, published last year by \uc2 McKinsey &Company\uc2 , of CEOs who have signed up for the UN global compact found that although 72 per cent said they thought corporate responsibility should be embedded fully into strategy and operations, only 50 per cent thought their companies actually did so. And, although 59 per cent of them thought corporate responsibility should be embedded into their global supply chains, only 27 per cent thought they were doing this.\par \par \uc2 The survey findings certainly apply to Asia, where most CEOs are not walking the talk says Vivek Kher, head of communications at \uc2 Suzlon Energy\uc2 , an Indian-based international wind energy company.\par \par \uc2 "The leadership is committed to taking every opportunity to talk about going green. But at the ground level there is no actual implementation. Up till now, CEOs haven't been really concerned about the planet. Mainly because Asia is still at the early stage and most emerging markets are yet to see industry impact on \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ."\par \par \uc2 He says the onus is on top leaders to push the environmental agenda within organisations. Industry leaders agree the region needs more forward-thinking CEOs who can set the tone.\par \par \uc2 "A fundamental shift in corporate culture or mindset can only take place with visionary leadership, and this has to be driven by the CEO," says April's Mr Franklin.\par \par \uc2 A recent report, "A new mindset for corporate sustainability"* underlines this point, saying corporations need to address sustainability at the highest levels. For instance, a board-level committee can be set up to advise directors and work closely with the management team to formulate and evaluate policies.\par \par \uc2 "Ensure that sustainability is a clearly stated value at every stage of your people management process, whether it's advertising for staff, hiring, induction, performance appraisal, remuneration or promotion," says the report.\par \par \uc2 Businesses in Asia are under increasing pressure to put sustainability at the heart of their operations, as governments across the region have started enforcing tough regulatory frameworks to ensure best practices. As consumers become more conscious of climate change, companies are left with no option but to change their ways of doing things.\par \par \uc2 "The traditional drivers of business strategy no longer apply to today's \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Companies now need to pay attention to the three Ps; profits, people and the planet, in order to grow and succeed in the long-term," says Mr Kher of \uc2 Suzlon Energy.\par \par \uc2 "Every business needs to see what footprint it's leaving on the planet, and that's the challenge for CEOs".\par \par \uc2 * {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://greenbiz.com/resources/resource/a-new-mindset-corporate-sustainability"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 http://greenbiz.com/resources/resource/a-new-mindset-corporate-sustainability }}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faa