par\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 City support for the Tories has soared under David Cameron's leadership, the party claimed on Wednesday, with membership of the Conservatives' network in the Square Mile doubling in the past three years.\par \par \uc2 The Conservative City Circle has 7,000 people on its database, and Conservative City Future - a sister organisation set up a year ago for professionals in their 20s - has signed up 1,000 lawyers and bankers.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 "You can chart the fortunes of the Conservatives by how many more people turn up to our drinks parties," George Osborne, the shadow chancellor, joked to a packed City Circle event close to the Tower of London last week.\par \par \uc2 The sheer number of guests - 1,200 accepted the invitation - was a dramatic contrast to the Tories' early years in opposition, when many in the City shunned them as unelectable.\par \par \uc2 Two years ago the Tories hailed a guest list of 500 for a City Circle event as a sign of progress in wooing back the corporate and City vote.\par \par \uc2 Mr Osborne has stressed the "huge effort" the Tories are putting into getting the City onside. He is conducting a behind-the-scenes campaign that has echoes of Labour's "prawn cocktail offensive" to allay City fears in the run-up to the 1997 election.\par \par \uc2 The wooing of the City is being undertaken in parallel with a drive to improve corporate relations outside the Square Mile. In a business relations unit set up by Mr Cameron, MPs chair groups that cover different sectors. Shadow ministers in the business and Treasury teams are conducting a relentless series of seminars, lunches and meetings, designed to ensure that the Tories' coverage ranges from multinational companies to small businesses in the regions.\par \par \uc2 Mr Cameron can claim a healthy flow of corporate donations to his party's coffers. But the Tories say their efforts are also bearing fruit in the form of non-financial offers of support from business.\par \par \uc2 "I'm amazed by the number of people, whether lawyers or bankers, coming forward and saying, 'Can we help?' " Richard Spring, the Tory MP who co-chairs the City Circle, told the Financial Times. "I can't overstate to you the extent to which this is now happening ... It has been a real change in the last two years or so."\par \par \uc2 Gordon Brown has proved an immeasurable help to the Conservative cause in the City, the Tories claim, because the government's tax measures have fuelled an appetite for political change.\par \par \uc2 The election of Boris Johnson should aid this process, according to Philip Hammond, shadow chief secretary to the Treasury. "It can only be good for us that we've got a Conservative mayor determined to work with business," he told the FT.\par \par \uc2 Mr Hammond also forecast that an increasing union influence on government policy would fuel business disenchantment with the government, as Labour makes policy concessions to its principal funder.\par \par \uc2 But the Tories should be wary of proclaiming victory prematurely. Employers' organisations say their members remain wary of Mr Cameron's rhetoric on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Leading business organisations are reserving judgment until the Tories fill the many gaps in their putative manifesto.\par \par \uc2 Alan Lewis, who chairs Conservative Business Relations, is confident this argument is being won. "We are the party that business can do business with," he says.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20080522_15470_139.xml\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gpol : \uc2 Domestic Politics | c42 : \uc2 Labor/Personnel Issues | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gpir : \uc2 Politics/International Relations | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfcpin : \uc2 FC&E Industry News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\r