t from the Big Ticks\par \par \uc2 McDonald's\uc2  knew it had an image problem as an employer when "McJob" made it into the Oxford English dictionary in 2001, to describe "an unstimulating, low-paid job with few prospects".\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The fast-food chain employs 67,000 people in the UK, many in their first job, and it has always provided training in transferable skills for their future careers.\par \par \uc2 But the gap between public perception and reality affected the confidence of its employees and deterred potential recruits.\par \par \uc2 The company responded with further improvements in the opportunities offered to staff, with extended flexible working practices, courses for English and maths qualifications and newly accredited management training.\par \par \uc2 Staff turnover has now fallen to an all-time low, the number of new starters leaving within 90 days is down by a third, confidence levels are up 10 cent and three-quarters of staff say they are proud to work for the restaurant chain.\par \par \uc2 More important, \uc2 McDonald's\uc2  has been able to challenge its detractors, by advertising the benefits of working for it with the slogan "Not bad for a McJob". As a result, it has been recognised with a "big tick" in the 2008 Business in the Community (BITC) awards for excellence, where this year's theme is best practice in finding and nurturing the talents essential for every organisation.\par \par \uc2 McDonald's\uc2  is one of four organisations with big ticks in the new BT Total Talent award category for their strategic approach to recognising talent and developing it.\par \par \uc2 The others are BAA's Heathrow operation, investment bank \uc2 Merrill Lynch\uc2  and the Scottish arm of PwC, the accountancy firm.\par \par \uc2 "The talent challenge is the next big thing," says Stephen Howard, BITC chief executive.\par \par \uc2 "The central issue for business is the struggle to find good people. The awards this year will focus on how we can unlock the country's talent. So much of it is about getting the best people and holding on to them."\par \par \uc2 Another category on the same theme is the Skills for Life award, sponsored by \uc2 Norfolk County Services.\uc2  Among the four organisations awarded a big tick this year for helping employees gain essential literacy, numeracy and language skills is \uc2 Ford Motor Company\uc2 , for its "Skills for Life" campaign to develop a skilled workforce at its Dagenham engine plant that can continuously improve the business.\par \par \uc2 Ford releases employees from the production line for short periods of one-to-one coaching until they are confident about sitting a national test. The tests are taken in quiet areas of the shop floor, invigilated by trained colleagues, and the results are given the same day. The coaches also work with management to improve communications and implement business improvement techniques.\par \par \uc2 Among the benefits have been a 92 per cent fall in severe accidents, production volumes up by a third, reduced energy consumption and improvements in staff morale. These improvements have helped safeguard 680 jobs, and added 450 new employees to support the \u163\'00\'A3170m investment in a new production facility at Dagenham.\par \par \uc2 "We have 2,500 people with the knowledge and power to develop our business," says Wallace Yearwood, manufacturing manager.\par \par \uc2 "All they need is the confidence and basic skills to help them facilitate change and growth."\par \par \uc2 Roy Harrison, an employee who has benefited and now hopes to become a group leader, explains why it has been so successful: "The one-to-one sessions (no feeling thick at the back of a classroom); works well with shifts and family life etc; not having to be tested in an intimidating \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ; flexible, personalised and friendly. Who would have thought it could be this simple!"\par \par \uc2 The other companies awarded big ticks this year in the Skills for Life category Boots, \uc2 npower\uc2  Operations Customer Services and Wiltan, which makes magnetic components in South Wales.\par \par \uc2 The talent theme is reflected in several categories, including the \uc2 Towers Perrin\uc2  Healthy Workplace award where the six companies with big ticks range from Grimsby Institute of Further and Higher Education to Ernst &Young, the accountancy firm. The three companies with big ticks in the Wates Employability award category for community programmes helping disadvantaged people into work include two builders Mansell and St George.\par \par \uc2 Last year's awards majored on climate change, where continued business interest is reflected in several categories this year. Big ticks in Man Group's International Climate Change award category have gone to retailers such as \uc2 Marks and Spencer\uc2 , \uc2 J Sainsbury\uc2 , Tesco and Co-operative Group. Nine companies are recognised in the \uc2 Lafarge\uc2  Cement UK Eco-Efficiency category, with big ticks for - among others - Adnams, the Southwold brewer, and law firm \uc2 Wragge &Co.\uc2  Cement UK Eco-Efficiency category, with big ticks for - among others - Adnams, the Southwold brewer, and law firm\par \par \uc2 The most popular category remains the Education award, sponsored by \uc2 Merrill Lynch\uc2 , with 17 big ticks altogether, for organisations ranging from FTSE 100 companies and City investment banks, to relative tiddlers such as National Physical Laboratory and Rangers Football Club.\par \par \uc2 Another 25 organisations have been re-accredited in this category. The Bupa Healthy Communities award produces the next highest group of big ticks, with eight for the likes of \uc2 Network Rail\uc2 , \uc2 Pfizer\uc2  and Eon.\par \par \uc2 Overall this year, there have been 268 new entries taking 106 big ticks, with another 107 re-accredited entries from 91 organisations. This is slightly down on last year when there were 283 new entries and 125 big ticks - a higher entry and a higher success rate. But BITC says the latter reflects the higher standards the peer assessors now expect in terms of impact and achievement.\par \par \uc2 Mr Howard detects no impact yet from the darkening skies over the business community, as the credit crunch pushes the economy into a slowdown that may distract businesses from their commitment to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . But he believes this year's focus on talent emphasises the importance of keeping a management eye on long-term issues even when the going gets tough.\par \par \uc2 "It is inevitable that companies will be much more cautious about how they spend their money. I hope they will realise that in a downturn, how they relate to their employees and communities will be more important than ever."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 ftnewspaper_20080529.xml|20080529L111.028\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertal