auto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 In 2003, Patrick Cescau sat down with fellow \uc2 Unilever\uc2  directors to hear a presentation from the Dove soap and cleansing products team. The Dove people had an idea for an advertising campaign that would feature women of all shapes and sizes rather than svelte models.\par \par \uc2 They showed the directors a film of girls talking about the pressure to look perfect, and how disappointed they were when they didn't. The girls in the film were the directors' daughters. Mr Cescau says watching his own teenager talk about her worries greatly affected him. He had no idea the Dove team had interviewed her, although his wife knew.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 "It suddenly becomes personal," he says. "You realise your own children are impacted by the beauty industry, how stressed they are by this image of unattainable beauty which is imposed on them every day - and the loss of self-esteem and other trouble going with it, anorexia and all of that."\par \par \uc2 The Dove campaign, which won two Grand Prix Cannes Advertising Awards, is touted by \uc2 Unilever\uc2  as an example of its philosophy of "doing well by doing good" - improving women's self-image while still selling plenty of soap and cleanser.\par \par \uc2 When he became chief executive of \uc2 Unilever\uc2  two years later, Mr Cescau was determined to take the responsible business philosophy even further. Not everyone approv\u173\'00\'ADed. He recalls the time of his first annual meeting in the role. "The company was not doing well. There was an article - I don't think it was in the FT - saying that I was draping myself in a flag of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  to excuse poor performance. I was so angry with that."\par \par \uc2 We are talking in 59-year-old Mr Cescau's office in \uc2 Unilever\uc2  House, the food and consumer goods group's newly refurbished London headquarters. Although \uc2 Unilever\uc2 's roots go back to Victorian times, Mr Cescau is its first sole chief ex\u173\'00\'ADec\u173\'00\'ADutive. The group previously had two - one based in the UK and one in the Netherlands.\par \par \uc2 While Mr Cescau, in open-necked pink shirt and dark blue jacket with elegant red check, is distinctly French, he is a \uc2 Unilever\uc2  lifer. After joining \uc2 Unilever\uc2  France 35 years ago, his career has taken him to Germany, the Netherlands, Indonesia, Portugal and the US. His multinational executive team has no British or Dutch nationals.\par \par \uc2 Yet his view of what he wishes to achieve harks back to \uc2 Unilever\uc2 's past. "I want to be remembered as the first CEO, the one that transformed \uc2 Unilever\uc2  and brought it back to its former glory," he says. What had \uc2 Unilever\uc2  lost before he took over? "We had forgotten some of our values, who we are, what makes us a different company. Our commitment to sustainability, to vitality, was always there but we were not recognising it as a source of strength and source of difference the way we do it today," he says.\par \par \uc2 Unilever\uc2  has been known for its community involvement since William Hesketh Lever, founder of Lever Brothers, began building a garden village for his workers at Port Sunlight on the River Mersey in 1888. When Lever Brothers mer\u173\'00\'ADged with Margarine Unie of the Netherlands to form \uc2 Unilever\uc2  in 1930, that philanthropic tradition continued.\par \par \uc2 In keeping with the modern trend, "sustainability" is the word Mr Cescau uses rather than philanthropy or even \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . "The point is sustainability cannot be simply about being nice. It has to be about business logic," he says.\par \par \uc2 First, \uc2 Unilever\uc2  cannot thrive in a degraded natural \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . "As I used to say: 'No fish, no fish finger. No water, no detergent powder.' " The "used to say" is because the fish business was sold in 2006.\par \par \uc2 Unilever\uc2 's concentrated detergent powder is a good example of both helping the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and improving profitability. "Yes, the margins are better for us. However, along the value chain of this product we use less water, less space, less plastic, less chemicals and packaging."\par \par \uc2 Second, the past few years have seen the rise of the "conscience consumer", someone who wants to know goods have been produced in ways that do not damage the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  or use child labour. Consumers, Mr Cescau says, are increasingly looking behind the brand. "Our children are becoming much more discerning in the way they use the internet, so they have a point of view on the company. Building reputational capital in this area is critical."\par \par \uc2 In pursuit of the conscience consumer, \uc2 Unilever\uc2  wants all the tea it buys to be certified as sustainable by the Rainforest Alliance. About half the tea it sells in the UK is now Rainforest Alliance-certified.\par \par \uc2 Third, \uc2 Unilever\uc2  expects much of its growth to come from developing-world consumers. The company has been influenced byCK Prahalad, the Indian-born, US-based business academic who has encouraged companies to look for the "fortune at the bottom of the pyramid".\par \par \uc2 Unilever\uc2  has long sold sachets rather than whole, unaffordable containers of detergent in Indian villages, where it has helped distributors set up in business. Prof Prahalad recently joinedMr Cescau as a non-executive director of Pearson, owner of the Financial Times.\par \par \uc2 Not everyone accepts \uc2 Unilever\uc2 's good faith. Greenpeace activists occupied \uc2 Unilever\uc2  House and other company sites in April in protest against the group's alleged damage to the Indonesian rainforests in pursuit of palm oil. "We have been working very seriously for the past couple of years to align industry behind palm oil sustainability. So being hit by the Greenpeace people was painful," Mr Cescau says.\par \par \uc2 Unilever\uc2  has worked with non-governmental organisations before. It asked Oxfam to assess its impact on the Indonesian economy, for ex\u173\'00\'ADample, and Mr Cescau hopes Greenpeace will become the company's partner on sustainable palm oil.\par \par \uc2 "We are going to see now whether they are going to work with us on this, because it is easier to be outside and criticise than to be inside and make choices and compromise to get results."\par \par \uc2 Will rising prices see the conscience consumers melt away? "It's a very good question, because at the same time as we see the conscience consumer rising, we equally see some finding difficulty paying a higher price." What will that do to Rainforest Alliance tea, which is presumably more expensive? "We're doing this for the long term," Mr Cescau insists.\par \par \uc2 And what about the doing well part? Isn't \uc2 Unilever\uc2  often seen as being in the shadow of \uc2 Procter &Gamble\uc2 ? After comfortably talking about sustainability, Mr Cescau does not much like this corporate turn in the conversation. "I knew the FT would be back," he smiles grimly. "As a matter of fact, over the past three years our total shareholder return performance has been better than Procter's."\par \par \uc2 Unilever\uc2  places its bets on the power of emerging economies\par \par \uc2 With so many of \uc2 Unilever\uc2 's hopes for growth focused on the developing world, chief executive Patrick Cescau insists economies such as India and China are in better shape than many people realise, writes Michael Skapinker. "Their macro-economic policies have been very stable, there is huge domestic demand, a middle class and a considerable increase in investment. There also has been a change in the flow and pattern of exports."\par \par \uc2 Emerging economies trade far more with each other, he says. "The story [of trade] between Brazil and China, for example, is just unbelievable. And because commodity prices have remained very high, there has continued to be money to invest into that trade. So while clearly there is going to be an impact, I think the idea that emerging markets are weak is a bit exaggerated."\par \par \uc2 However, rising energy prices are affecting \uc2 Unilever.\uc2  "It impacts the input cost of our product substantially - fuel directly, and indirectly the petrochemicals that we use in the active ingredients for our shampoos and our deter\par \par \uc2 gents. Packaging is affected, fertilisers. And then, of course, all of our suppliers experience these cost increases themselves and see their margins being reduced, and hence look at the opportunity themselves to recover costs."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \l