djustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Enterprising Britain\par \par \uc2 W hen the elders of Garmser in the Afghan province of Helmand were seeking to restore security to the region, they asked the provincial governor for help to resume market gardening. Growing food would provide work for hundreds of people, support their families and provide an alternative to the Taliban. All they required was a modest amount of finance to restore water supplies and generate power - but at that time, in 2006, the governor had no funds to help.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 For Brigadier Ed Butler, then com-mander of British forces in southern Afghanistan, it was a tale he had heard time and again in his army career - in Iraq, in Africa and in the Balkans. In his view, government organisations and non-government organisations are good at long-term projects, but for quick, short-term intervention only companies have the agility and the entrepreneurial skills.\par \par \uc2 "A business could have kickstarted the local economy in Garmser," he says. "It would have taken fighters off the streets and provided money to restabilise the community."\par \par \uc2 But while many international companies donate money to NGOs in the emerging or frontier markets where they operate, few become directly involved. This, he believes, is due to lack of expertise. But by intervening, Brig Butler asserts, businesses could encourage local stability as well as en-hance their reputations.\par \par \uc2 He is stepping down as chief of the UK's Joint Force Operations to become managing director of Corporates for Crisis, a company set up to help businesses become directly involved in development and humanitarian operations. CforC will help companies use their business skills to identify, design and implement community projects, rather than simply writing cheques for charities.\par \par \uc2 "We will be a genuine 'boots and suits' organisation," says Brig Butler. "Our teams will provide an unusual mix of entrepreneurial business minds, humanitarian conviction, development expertise, military planning and operational precision."\par \par \uc2 Support for organisations that work in remote or difficult places, such as that offered by CforC is a growing business (see below).\par \par \uc2 The idea for CforC was dreamt up by Christopher James, who founded Hakluyt in 1994 after leaving MI6, to provide strategic advice and intelligence for companies. Talking to the chairmen and chief executives of Fortune 50 companies after the Asian tsunami of December 2004, he found they had donated millions to the relief operations but had no idea how the money had been spent.\par \par \uc2 When he retired in 2006, he decided to find a way to bring the corporate world more directly into such efforts. "Rather than just giving money, they could invest in the affected people and communities - helping them set themselves up again," he says.\par \par \uc2 Brig Butler is one of three directors Mr James recruited to turn this idea into a business that would intervene in crises and in fragile post-conflict areas. The others are Sahar Hashemi, the serial entrepreneur who founded Coffee Republic with her brother Bobby, and Hugo Slim, who has more than 20 years' experience in the humanitarian sector.\par \par \uc2 "I needed someone from the NGO world and someone who understood business," says Mr James, CforC chairman. "When I was searching for operations expertise, I rang Ed to pick his brains - and he said he was interested in a change of career."\par \par \uc2 After 25 years in the army, inc-luding a spell in the British special forces, Brig Butler was interested in a job that would let him see more of his young family and he found the concept of CforC particularly intriguing. "Having spent a lot of time in crisis situations, I have seen the big gap between what the military is able to do and what the inter-national community has to offer. If the army can create a secure \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , business can quickly restore activity by employing people, paying their wages and supporting their families."\par \par \uc2 Mr Slim says he has seen exactly the same problem from the NGO perspective, while working for Save The Children and the UN, serving on the Oxfam council and acting as consultant to organisations such as the British Red Cross. "Companies could be incredibly important players as strategic partners for NGOs in emerging markets," he says.\par \par \uc2 He believes there are several stages where CforC can assist. The first is when a company wants to enter a market, where offering its services as a "good corporate citizen" might help ease arrival. Once there, well-targeted \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  work can help win the approval of the local community - part of its "licence to operate". A third stage can arise when companies fall foul of local interests and need to re-establish their credentials. Last, when the time comes to move on, a good exit ensures the company's image is enhanced when it enters new markets later.\par \par \uc2 Ms Hashemi sees her role as bringing an entrepreneur's eye to the needs of corporate clients and helping to bring them closer to the communities they operate in. Companies "often don't get the chance to use their entrepreneurial DNA", she says. "If they can go beyond aid to building infrastructure and sustainable businesses, they can provide the tools for people to help themselves."\par \par \uc2 CforC says it has met the chairmen or chief executives of more than 20 FTSE 100 companies, and is involved in several assignments. Two projects are already under way in Africa. Backed by a handful of private investors, two of whom have invested sums totalling just over \u163\'00\'A31m, it ex-pects to build a staff of 20 within three years, and a much larger network of experts who can be deployed to countries on particular projects.\par \par \uc2 "Not all companies understand how these countries work," says Brig Butler. "Even in Afghanistan, the violence affects only 10 per cent of the country.\par \par \uc2 "There is plenty of space for business if they approach such markets with the right help."\par \par \uc2 Demand grows for taking companies out of the comfort zone\par \par \uc2 The growing market for supporting organisations that work in difficult locations is ripe for consolidation, says Tim Mitchell. Formerly strategic development chief for Kroll, the global risk consultancy firm, he is now deputy chief executive of Exploration Logistics, a British company with ambitions to expand.\par \par \uc2 "Demand for oil is driving a big expansion of exploration into areas previously thought too difficult," says Mr Mitchell. A Canadian lawyer, he was behind more than 25 acquisitions and other ventures between 2002 and 2004, the year \uc2 Marsh &McLennan\uc2  bought Kroll for $1.9bn(\u163\'00\'A3955m).\par \par \uc2 Exlogs was founded 22 years ago by a former member of the Special Boat Squadron, the Royal Navy's special forces unit, and a guide with the British Antarctic Survey. Initially it provided medical services to oil and gas companies operating in challenging environments, adding mine clearance in 1988 and driver training in the late 1990s.\par \par \uc2 With more than 1,000 medics, consultants, training and field personnel, its revenues have climbed from \u163\'00\'A318m in the year to April 2007 to an expected \u163\'00\'A330m-plus in the year to 2009.\par \par \uc2 Exlogs has just bought a company supplying medical services to oil, gas and mining companies in the Canadian Arctic. Other small acquisitions will follow, leading to the raising of new capital within six to 12 months.\par \par \uc2 But there is no difficulty in financing acquisitions, Mr Mitchell says. "There is no link to the standard financial cycle. Growth is driven by conflict issues and mainly the price of oil - not the present price spike, but the need to secure long-term supplies."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 ftnewspaper_20080730.xml|20080730L112.133\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspal