rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The marketing model of Formula One has not changed a great deal since 1968, when the Lotus team committed the then subversive act of putting a sponsor's logo and branding on its car. It was the tobacco brand Gold Leaf and the livery of the car was completely given over to the brand. The rest of the teams quickly followed.\par \par \uc2 Forty years later, "stickers on cars" is still the model by which sponsors get their brands in front of the cameras. Most F1 teams derive about half of their income from sponsorship and many juggle the opposing needs of diverse sponsors, with each part of the car having a rate card.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Honda sees itself as an innovative company and is now in the second year of a radical marketing initiative - radical because it features no sponsor logos at all.\par \par \uc2 With the Earthdreams concept, Honda is making \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  the centrepiece of its marketing proposition. It claims it is drawing the attention of F1 fans to the changing world and especially to environmental concerns.\par \par \uc2 This is a highly subversive act - in many ways more so than Lotus's Gold Leaf deal; a leading manufacturer in one of the world's least environmentally friendly sports is bringing the debate about global warming and climate change to F1's doorstep.\par \par \uc2 To many in the sport it is an unwelcome debate. But Honda's management reasoned that the debate was going to come to F1 anyway, so the company decided to market itself as the early adopter. And now they are in the process of signing up corporate sponsors that want to align themselves with the Earthdreams message.\par \par \uc2 Team boss Nick Fry explains that the team had three choices when its partnership with the Lucky Strike cigarette brand came to an end in 2006: "To continue with traditional marketing, which would have given the car over to a variety of other companies ... to market Honda, or to do something different.\par \par \uc2 "The first option didn't make a lot of sense to us, because the F1 programme is immensely expensive and has the ability to communicate to in excess of 600m people around the world. Our logic was: 'Why would we want to give away our prime asset - the car - for a percentage, although not small, certainly not the majority of the cost of the programme, to other people?'\par \par \uc2 "We decided to go with the third route, which would be more worthwhile. The item at the top of most people's agenda and which aligned most closely with Honda's values was the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 "Right from the formation of the company, Mr Honda was very passionate that the only things which came out of the factory were the products and that there should be minimum waste and minimum pollution."\par \par \uc2 Honda launched the Earthcar concept in 2007 - a blue vehicle with a map of the earth painted on it. It was a rather fuzzy message to start with and was not delivered in a particularly convincing way by the drivers who mumbled about switching lights off at night.\par \par \uc2 The response evolved pretty much as the research had told them it would, with much of the press and the public cynical about Honda's green credentials.\par \par \uc2 But the concept sparked the interest of many others. The public was invited to make donations for worthwhile projects and $2.2m was raised. This year, the original concept has evolved into Earthdreams, which supports a network of nine environmental projects around the work, each receiving about $47,000.\par \par \uc2 Vitally, Earthdreams is also generating a database of "concerned" fans which is constantly growing and which is of great use to the projects. These include the Marine Stewardship Council, which has established a global standard for sustainable fishing practices, the Lighthouse Foundation, which targets youth homelessness in Australia and the Spirit of Soccer project, which uses soccer coaching as a way of teaching landmine safety in Cambodia.\par \par \uc2 All the charities selected focus on investing in and developing people. Honda says this message is consistent with its rationale for being in F1 - to train engineers.\par \par \uc2 Honda claims that rather than talking vaguely about saving the world, it is setting out to do something about it, albeit on a modest scale - or as the company puts it, "powering dreams one lap at a time".\par \par \uc2 But with an annual team budget of about $560m a year, the Honda board is keen to offset some of the cost by reintroducing sponsors, ideally by aligning major companies that want to share in the initiative.\par \par \uc2 "We can offer [sponsors] not just the stickers on the cars, and the message 'We are in Grand Prix racing', which everyone can offer," says Fry. "We can offer a message about what our company is doing.\par \par \uc2 "Many other companies around the world are doing fantastic things in terms of CSR; the problem is how to communicate this. What we are doing in F1 with the Earthdreams project is a way of doing both."\par \par \uc2 When the Earthcar was launched, it caused unhappiness among some other teams because it led their sponsors to ask, "What is our position on this?"\par \par \uc2 But with the 2009 F1 regulations driving the sport towards more environmentally sustainable technologies, such as the hybrid energy regeneration system called Kers and the FIA, the sport's governing body, demanding new rules that will limit the engines by how much power they can derive from a fixed amount of fuel, the sport has begun speeding towards the tipping point on sustainability anyway.\par \par \uc2 "Clearly, we had a degree of hostility," says Fry. "We were undermining the market, but a couple of teams understood straight away.\par \par \uc2 "In many ways, we got F1 off the hook a bit. We were the people talking about the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  in a frankly not very environmentally friendly sport. Someone had to do it, so within the paddock we got a few quiet pats on the back, because it was like: 'It's not for us, but someone's got to do it and thank God you are.'"\par \par \uc2 The message would be a lot more effective if it were on a winning car and sadly Earthdreams has coincided with a trough of poor performance from the racing team.\par \par \uc2 It will be interesting to see which will be the first to dominate in F1, the Honda team or the debate on global warming.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20080902_18135_346.xml\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ad