aauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 It was a breath of fresh air when Sir Nicholas Stern published "Economics of Climate Change"; it was a sign that industry's views on sustainable management are finally shifting for the better.\par \par \uc2 Sir Nicholas's argument that it is cheaper for companies to do something, rather than nothing, when it comes to climate change vindicates our efforts at BT, where we have been reducing our carbon footprint since 1992.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 As a consumer of around 0.7 per cent of the UK's electricity, BT has long sought ways to reduce its carbon footprint for both environmental and cost reasons.\par \par \uc2 Last year we announced plans to spend \u163\'00\'A3250m building wind farms, the single biggest renewable energy investment outside of the energy sector. By doing so we hope to provide 25 per cent of our own energy needs, with the hope of sourcing half of our total power used from non-fossil fuels by 2016.\par \par \uc2 We have also been overhauling our data centres to make them as "green" as possible and have been educating our 110,000 employees around the world to make them more environmentally aware and to engage them in the fight to combat climate change.\par \par \uc2 However, for companies to reduce their carbon footprint and become better corporate citizens, they also need to look beyond their own four walls, and work with their suppliers. You are only as strong as your weakest link and if your suppliers are failing to change, the likelihood is that it will affect you.\par \par \uc2 This year, we have been involved in \u163\'00\'A32.2bn worth of bids, in which customers require us to show our \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  credentials. Were it not for the fact that we were already working with our own suppliers to build a green supply chain, the chances are we wouldn't have done quite so well in our negotiations.\par \par \uc2 However, BT's approach to building its green supply chain has not been to seek green suppliers, but to have our current suppliers go green with us. We want to help our current suppliers reduce their carbon footprints and, as such, reduce the carbon footprints of the products and services they supply to us. We want to ensure that every new generation of equipment we hand out to customers is more energy efficient than its predecessor.\par \par \uc2 In addition to building requirements into our procurement contracts that consider the environmental impact of products from manufacture to disposal, we are also surveying our suppliers to ascertain whether they have a climate change plan in place.\par \par \uc2 More than 1,800 of our largest suppliers have been compulsory surveyed and graded on where they are on their green journey. For some technology contracts, where the need to deliver the lowest carbon product or service is critical, then only our best performing suppliers will be chosen as partners. We work with our other suppliers to help them get where they need to be.\par \par \uc2 The same goes with both small business and corporate customers: as part of our consultancy we offer them carbon impact assessments to measure how energy intensive or environmentally friendly their business processes are.\par \par \uc2 Admittedly there are costs to put this in place, but BT's energy efficiency projects have the potential to deliver \u163\'00\'A360m in energy savings and reduce CO2 emissions by 200,000 tonnes.\par \par \uc2 By working with suppliers on our One IT project and by reducing computer servers, we have been able to achieve a net saving of 22GW hours per year in energy usage. This translates to around \u163\'00\'A31.8m or around 3,110 metric tonnes of carbon per year.\par \par \uc2 However, the global companies require global consistency and one thing international businesses lack is a clear way of measuring their impact on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  globally. At the moment, too many countries measure their carbon impact in different ways, making it very difficult for companies and their suppliers to be consistent globally.\par \par \uc2 The motivations for a green supply chain are obvious: it ensures a better and more sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ; it also saves businesses money. As customers become more environmentally aware, having a green organisation and supply chain will also act as a differentiator when on the tender list.\par \par \uc2 The challenge now is to ensure that the credentials are consistent across the globe.\par \par \uc2 Donna Young is head of \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and climate change for BT Group.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard 