down the list, writes Daniel Thomas\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The green agenda is at risk of being sidelined by the credit crisis, in spite of attempts to keep issues alive in the commercial property industry. The environmental impact of commercial property is undeniable, with about half of all Britain's carbon emissions associated with buildings, according to government figures.\par \par \uc2 Corporate property is thought to be responsible for as much as a fifth of global CO emissions, through energy use, waste and water production. This is equivalent of the average annual car use of 90m people.\par \par \uc2 With almost 50 per cent of a company's CO emissions believed to be produced by its real estate, it is no surprise that property offers one of the most direct ways for those with stringent \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  codes to make a difference.\par \par \uc2 However, a recent study of more than 100 directors responsible for real estate by \uc2 Knight Frank\uc2  showed that concerns about the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and energy efficiency had fallen to the bottom of the agenda.\par \par \uc2 On a list of the 10 most important factors when considering a building, sustainability was 10th. The top issues were rental cost and staff retention, perhaps unsurprisingly given the pressures on many businesses as the economy stalls.\par \par \uc2 With tenants no longer focused as much on the desirability for green buildings, the impetus could also be lost among developers and property owners, who may be worried about higher costs in a market where prices are already under pressure.\par \par \uc2 It had been hoped that higher rents would be possible on modern green buildings. But with costs up by as much as a quarter, says consultancy Savills, and commercial property hit by taxes such as empty rates, there is less incentive for developers to go "green".\par \par \uc2 A survey of the attitudes of the UK's leading investors by \uc2 GVA Grimley\uc2  showed that "very modest" progress had been made towards increasing the sustainability of property within investment portfolios over the past year.\par \par \uc2 To a certain extent, the industry is having to reform some of its polluting ways because of increasingly strict regulations, although some feel the UK government's policy has not been effective.\par \par \uc2 It has introduced various means of improving the carbon footprint of buildings, including mandatory energy performance certificates, which landlords have to obtain to provide an energy rating of their buildings, as well as the non-compulsory Breeam (Building Research Establishment Environmental Assessment Method) ratings.\par \par \uc2 Another industry initiative is the so-called green leases, which aim to help create a partnership between landlord and tenant in cutting emissions. Hermes, for example, is redrawing many of its leases to include "green" clauses that encourage tenants to help reduce the impact of its buildings.\par \par \uc2 Siobhan Cross, a property partner at \uc2 Pinsent Masons\uc2  a law firm, says the most important event will be the government's climate change bill, which includes targets for 26 to 32 per cent carbon emissions reduction by 2020 and 60 per cent by 2050.\par \par \uc2 Ms Cross says the bill includes a mandatory carbon trading scheme that will affect large owners and occupiers with direct electricity bills of more than \u163\'00\'A3500,000 a year.\par \par \uc2 However, there has been criticism of government efforts to date. Savills says what is lacking is a requirement to occupy a property in a more sustainable way, rather than simply rely on the developer.\par \par \uc2 "There is still no evidence that 'greener' buildings attract higher rents or keener yields but, in the face of changing consumer attitudes, increased occupier demand and government pressure, this may change," adds Charles Woollam, director at DTZ, one of the world's largest real estate advisers.\par \par \uc2 He is also sceptical about green leases, saying they have implications on valuation. "Too tight, lower rents. Too light, unenforceable," he says.\par \par \uc2 A cross-party parliamentary group, the All Party Urban Development Group, backed by the British Property Federation, has criticised the government's green policy as favouring easy headlines. It says there is too much focus on making new buildings carbon-neutral, and not enough on existing buildings, which it says make up 99 per cent of the problem.\par \par \uc2 With the expectation that up to 70 per cent of nondomestic properties will be still functioning by 2050, existing buildings are an area where the biggest carbon savings can be made.\par \par \uc2 Part of the problem is the lack of a single international benchmark to assess the impact of buildings on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , according to the committee, although there have been attempts to do so.\par \par \uc2 Various initiatives have been introduced, most recently an "\b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  code", which has the support of bodies such as the Confederation of British Industry, the employers' organisation, and Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors, as well as companies such as \uc2 Barclays\uc2  and BP.\par \par \uc2 With initiatives such as this, at least the first steps of the debate seem to be being won - the realisation that green is here to stay. And with that will come the property industry's traditional entrepreneurial desire to make money out of it.\par \par \uc2 Fund managers predict that higher rates of return will eventually come from the lower operating costs of \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 -friendly buildings as well as from tenants willing to pay more for renting "sustainable spaces". One idea being explored by many groups is a green property fund, such as the one being considered by fund manager Climate Change fund, comprising investments in \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 -friendly buildings. The theory goes that if occupiers were willing to pay more money, then such a fund could become more profitable, although others argue that all property funds will end up being "green" by deault.\par \par \uc2 Outside property, funds have been investing in "green" businesses for a number of years, with listed green equity funds having sometimes traded at higher levels than their peers.\par \par \uc2 Andy Schofield, head of responsible property investment at Henderson, says the fund manager recently completed the first stage of a review of 171 buildings within its UK property portfolio - looking at the environmental impact of each and how it could be improved.\par \par \uc2 He imagines that the increasing concentration on "green" buildings will create a two-tier real estate industry. Henderson believes that ensuring its buildings are sustainable is important to securing long-term future income from its assets and that fund managers attempting to use a weakening property market as an excuse to sideline their commitment to sustainability do so at their peril.\par \par \uc2 To an extent, developers are ensuring new office buildings are "future-proofed" with the latest energy efficient technology.\par \par \uc2 But it is the existing stock that remains the problem. In a market in which tenants are finding plenty of choice, the more polluting - and normally old-fashioned - buildings will command less rent, regardless of government initiatives, and so be worth less to their owners.\par \par \uc2 Serious long-term property investors will need to address these issues. How fast this happens is the question, however, and for all the steps forward in recent years, some of the impetus has been lost, as efforts turn to surviving the downturn.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 ftnewspaper_20081006.xml|20081006S103.289\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 kfr : \uc2 Knight Frank\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i834 : \uc2 Real Estate Agents/Brokers | icre : \uc2 Construction/Real Estate | ireest : \uc2 Real Estate\cell \pard \ql \li