n looks at the tobacco company's focus on sustainability and its enthusiasm for videoconferencing\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 When it comes to negotiating with \uc2 British American Tobacco\uc2 's technology suppliers, CIO Phil Cook is not simply looking to drive a tough bargain, he's looking to drive a green one, too.\par \par \uc2 He says the company is even willing to pay more - in some circumstances - for technologies that help it to live up to its \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  (CSR) commitments to the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 At the same time, it increasingly expects companies tendering for its business to provide robust figures on the environmental impact associated with their products and services.\par \par \uc2 "I strongly believe that CSR doesn't begin and end at your own garden fence. We can't declare ourselves green unless our suppliers can too," he says.\par \par \uc2 That is important for a company heavily reliant on outsourcing to run a huge network of data centres scattered throughout the world. Its three tier-one data centres (in Singapore, Frankfurt and Portalegre, Brazil) are all run on its behalf by third-party partners, as are many of the 200-plus tier-two and tier-three facilities it uses worldwide.\par \par \uc2 "We don't just ask about price. We want providers to compete on environmental selling points, too: on the hardware they propose to deploy and use on our behalf, on how that hardware will be powered and cooled, and on their ability to get the most from that hardware through consolidation and virtualisation," he says.\par \par \uc2 "We expect them to have answers to these questions - it's part of the response we're looking for from any company we're considering doing business with."\par \par \uc2 Data to back up those answers is vital, he adds, "because IT vendors will only live up to the green IT promise if CIOs push them".\par \par \uc2 BAT's focus on environmental sustainability applies equally to IT equipment at the end of its life: the company has about 40,000 desktop and laptop PCs and replaces them every three years or so. As many of these as possible are recycled and donated to charity, says Mr Cook.\par \par \uc2 As yet, there is no global standard at BAT for the disposal of PCs, "but in future I would expect us to have guidelines for all of our operations".\par \par \uc2 The real jewel in BAT's green IT crown, however, is its telepresence system, implemented over the past year at a cost of more than \u163\'00\'A33m. According to David Sampson, head of IT at BAT's London headquarters, this is where the company is notching up its biggest gains in environmental terms.\par \par \uc2 "We operate in 180 countries, so air travel has historically been a big area of cost and environmental impact for us," he explains.\par \par \uc2 By replacing many trips with virtual meetings, held in the company's telepresence suites, he estimates a saving of 285 medium and long-haul flights, knocking \u163\'00\'A3300,000 off the the company's annual travel bill.\par \par \uc2 "And if you factor in the management time wasted by executives packing their bags, travelling to airports, clearing security and sitting on flights, you're looking at a figure closer to \u163\'00\'A3800,000," he adds.\par \par \uc2 In terms of carbon avoidance, figures have proved harder to calculate, "since those flights would take off and land whether or not there are passengers from BAT on them". However, he is researching the best way of estimating it.\par \par \uc2 The roll-out of the Teliris system, deployed in partnership with Orange Business Services, kicked off with the opening of telepresence suites in Australia, Hong Kong, London, Brazil, Canada and Mexico in February 2008. Over the course of this year, more suites are scheduled to open in Japan, Malaysia, Russia, Germany and South Africa.\par \par \uc2 "We work on the basis that people are adults and can decide for themselves whether a telepresence session is a viable alternative to a face-to-face meeting - no one is forced to opt for the telepresence option," he says. Usage figures, however, show that many do: the system is in use for about 40 per cent of the average working day at BAT.\par \par \uc2 What has helped in its uptake, says Mr Sampson, is the way telepresence systems can give the impression all users are sitting in the same room.\par \par \uc2 "A great deal of attention has been paid to the psychology of the collaborative experience. So each suite conforms to a standard, using the same backgrounds, chairs and lighting. Cameras and microphones use vectoring technology to ensure that participants can look at and speak to each other directly.\par \par \uc2 "All the visual and audio clues are geared towards immediacy, fluidity and coherency of conversation," he says.\par \par \uc2 Mr Cook admits these successes have typically been won on a task-by-task basis, but says an over-arching green IT strategy is under development. "It's a massive task but a necessary one. Green IT will not just be a piece of paper at BAT."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjus