15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Financial Times (FT.Com)\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 FTCOM\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2008 The Financial Times Limited. All rights reserved \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 In recent years, business schools have embraced the idea of "\b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 " and "sustainability". Centres, institutes, programmes and initiatives have sprung up, websites and brochures trumpet business schools' dedication to serving society, ethics, managing the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social entrepreneurship.\par \par \uc2 A new breed of MBA student is focused on "doing well by doing good", demanding that more attention be given to the world's social and environmental challenges.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Yet, despite the apparent surge in activity, little has changed within schools. Core courses continue to be organised along conventional functional lines - finance, accounting, marketing, operations, strategy - with little exposure to emerging challenges such as climate change, global poverty or inequity.\par \par \uc2 Professors pursue narrowly prescribed research agendas with the aim of publishing their work in a small set of academic "A" journals. Careers are made (or broken) based on publication "hits" in these journals, along with recommendations by peer faculty at other universities, rather than the relevance or impact of the ideas in the real world.\par \par \uc2 The truth is that the apparent "greening" of business schools is a form of "greenwashing". Even the most highly ranked of such programmes consist of a few dedicated faculty and support staff.\par \par \uc2 Rather than being integrated into the fabric of the business school, sustainability initiatives "hang off the side" of the existing academic edifice. High-profile donors may draw attention to these programmes, yet few have penetrated the entrenched interests of the function-based senior faculty.\par \par \uc2 All, however, is not lost. Indeed, courses focused on sustainable enterprise and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  are gaining momentum and are among the largest enrolment electives in many business schools. Core courses can rather easily integrate many of these challenges by simply including sustainability challenges as "contexts" for teaching core material. For example, operations can teach life cycle management as part of supply chain management and finance can teach clean technology innovation through the lens of "real options".\par \par \uc2 For nearly 20 years, I have been dedicated to developing programmes on "sustainable enterprise" in US business schools. In the early years, sustainability initiatives were little more than small subcultures that were allowed to exist as long as they did not syphon resources away from more "central" (read functional) areas of focus.\par \par \uc2 In the past several years, however, there has been a noticeable increase in the demand for this content, not only among MBA students, but also from companies themselves. Mainstream companies have made \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and sustainability core to their corporate and competitive strategies. And serving the 4bn poor at the "base of the pyramid" is seen as one of the most important potential drivers of future growth. "Social responsibility" as corporate obligation is giving way to societal problems as "corporate opportunities".\par \par \uc2 By framing the world's social and environmental challenges as new business opportunities, we have succeeded in attracting the "best and the brightest" MBA students. Indeed, at Cornell's Johnson School, our Center for Sustainable Global Enterprise has served as a magnet for some of the best prospective MBA students as well as some of the best companies.\par \par \uc2 As the centre's profile increases, it garners faculty interest. Indeed, professors from the school and across the university are attracted to the intellectual agenda associated with sustainable enterprise (which cuts across conventional disciplinary lines). If we continue on this path, the world's social and environmental challenges just might become better integrated into the DNA of business schools.\par \par \uc2 Stuart L Hart is \uc2 SC Johnson\uc2  Chair in Sustainable Global Enterprise at the Johnson Graduate School of Management, Cornell University.\par \par \uc2 The Soapbox column is open to professors, students and others interested in the future of business schools.\par \par \uc2 To comment on this article go to {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.ft.com/soapbox"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.ft.com/soapbox}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20081013_7877_274.xml\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\ad