s and how the industry is faring in the downturn\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Going green and going mean. These are the watchwords for the convention, congress and large meeting segment of Europe's meetings, incentives and exhibitions market (Mice).\par \par \uc2 In times of recession, customers invariably want more for less and the global meetings market is no exception.\par \par \uc2 Most travel businesses have no doubt that testing times lie ahead, given the current state of the global economy.\par \par \uc2 Karen Penney, vice-president of Business Solutions for American Express Global Commercial Card, says the European hotel market is entering a new phase, with slower demand and lower rates. Rates are decreasing in most of the region's financial centres, such as London, Frankfurt, Paris, Geneva and Edinburgh, she notes.\par \par \uc2 However, Roger Tondeur, president of MCI, a self-styled "global association, communications and event management company" that organises some 3,000 meetings a year around the world, says there is no trend to reduce meetings - which are vital to the hotel industry.\par \par \uc2 Countries such as Brazil, Russia, India and China are contributing huge growth to the global market. China alone, he says, has some 200 convention centres under construction.\par \par \uc2 "In Europe and the US, we are feeling a slowdown. After years of double-digit growth in corporate meetings, year on year, we are feeling stagnation but not a reduction."\par \par \uc2 Mr Tondeur says the big trend is towards \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  (CSR) and, specifically, greener conferences.\par \par \uc2 He explains: "As mitigating the impact of meetings on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  becomes important, and our customers recognise the value of meetings, price is not the deciding factor in selecting an agency of choice but more strategic aspects, such as CSR, come into play."\par \par \uc2 Mr Tondeur points out that when a large company moves 14,000 people to a destination for three days, it has an enormous environmental impact.\par \par \uc2 "Hotels and convention centres are starting to understand the impact of their carbon footprint. Hence, we are slowly seeing properties investing in innovative solutions, such as solar heating and recycling."\par \par \uc2 Jerad Bacher, head of sales at the Dubai Convention Bureau, points out that much of the industry, by its nature, has a long view: "The conventions we are organising today will not take place until 2010 and beyond."\par \par \uc2 He says that Europe may have its travails, but Dubai can attract business from elsewhere - Russia and Asia in particular. He adds: "Most of our work is so far in the future that we haven't seen any falling off yet in business.\par \par \uc2 "Dubai has pretty much the highest hotel occupancy rates of anywhere in the world and room inventories will double in the near future."\par \par \uc2 But, with a note of caution, he also says: "We have to sell value as we are selling into the future. Convention planners are much more demanding now. They are looking for much better packages from a city or destination.\par \par \uc2 "More and more, we are seeing requests for financial support from suppliers and our budgets are the same."\par \par \uc2 Ian Scott, director of the UK and Ireland office of the Dubai Department of Tourism and Commerce Marketing, says more than 1m business visitors attended exhibitions and conferences at the Dubai International Convention and Exhibition Centre last year, making it one of the world's most popular.\par \par \uc2 The Mice industry contributes significantly to the United Arab Emirates' tourism sector, representing nearly 30 per cent of GDP.\par \par \uc2 In Europe, Germany leads the way in large meetings, conferences and conventions and no country has more experience of keeping the show on the road when budgets are tight.\par \par \uc2 Cost-saving potential partly explains why German hotel operators are going green. Germans feel a strong sense of responsibility for the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , but they are also responding to growing customer pressure.\par \par \uc2 This is confirmed by Imex, a leading industry trade fair. A survey it conducted this year showed Mice producers are increasingly interested in sustainability and CSR.\par \par \uc2 Stephen Walker, UK head of Mice for \uc2 Starwood Hotels\uc2  and Resorts, says the most notable trend in the market for conventions, large meetings and events is the constant need for flexibility.\par \par \uc2 "The physical venue needs to provide the latest in technology - wireless internet access, plasma screens, ergonomic work stations, et cetera, and the service needs to be fast, efficient and hassle-free."\par \par \uc2 Mr Walker says venues need to be able to work closely with conference and event organisers to offer flexible arrangements that meet both business requirements and budgetary constraints.\par \par \uc2 He adds: "Pricing needs to be simple and transparent. We need to be clear from the start what exactly is included in the delegate rate to make the booking process as easy as possible for conference and event organisers."\par \par \uc2 Mr Tondeur is hoping that the cloud over the world's financial markets may have at least one silver lining: that the meetings industry, which is inextricably linked to the hotel and hospitality sectors, can recruit skilled employees in the aftermath of job losses in the financial sector.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.mci-group.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 www.mci-group.com}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 ftnewspaper_20081013.xml|20081013S111.255\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 miceg : \uc2 Mice Group PLC\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i8395411 : \uc2 Convention/Trade Shows | iadv : \uc2 Advertising/Public Relations/Marketing | imark : \uc2 Marketing\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-1