ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Open EMBA programmes may be in the majority, but single-company courses retain their supporters - and may be the better option in certain cases.\par \par \uc2 "The great big, behemoth [single-company] programmes are probably on the way out," says Chris Bones, dean of Henley Business School at the University of Reading, in the UK. "Sheep-dipping large numbers of people through a reasonably generic qualification is not, I think, the best investment you can make if you are going to do it without a purpose."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 On the other hand, he says, there is always a role for development of talent on a single-company basis, whether it comes with a qualification attached, as with an EMBA or a more function-specific EMSc, or not, as in a short, tailored course of executive education.\par \par \uc2 The choice, says Prof Bones, is a strategic issue that will depend on the most important driver for the company: "Is this aligned to a strategic change in the organisation, so you want the programme to be very focused, tailored, and part of your competitive edge? Or is it part of a capability-building agenda where what you want to do is learn from and network with other people, and other sectors. They are two very different approaches, and both are right, at different times in an organisation's development."\par \par \uc2 Henley runs two single-company EMBA programmes, for Danfoss Group, the Danish manufacturer of mechanical and electronic products, and the medical division of Johor Corporation, a Malaysian conglomerate. Heads of agreement have just been signed with a third company, says Prof Bones.\par \par \uc2 Both Danfoss and Johor can fill a class that would ideally be 30-strong - enough to achieve high levels of interaction, he says. Being big enough to do that is a prerequisite for a single-company EMBA.\par \par \uc2 That is no problem for IBM, whose Europe-wide programme has been running for 12 years, moving in 2006 from Henley to Warwick Business School. IBM sends about 100 people on it each year, in two intakes.\par \par \uc2 Mia Vanstraelen, director of human resources at IBM Benelux, says IBM has tried an open programme in the past, working with a couple of other companies, but did not find it more beneficial.\par \par \uc2 "We invest in this type of programme because we really believe in fostering talent, and making sure our best employees have excellent opportunities to learn, while at the same time supporting the cultural and leadership changes which we are making at the company," she says.\par \par \uc2 Prof Bones says one main advantage of Henley's single-company EMBA is that the customer gets a huge opportunity to tailor cases, material and connectivity to its business, within a structure that is unchanged from the standard EMBA - thus retaining the same quality assurance that comes from accreditation and a high ranking.\par \par \uc2 The key drawback of single-company EMBA programmes, as viewed by schools that concentrate on the open version, is the perceived lack of diversity among the cohort.\par \par \uc2 "At the Kellogg School, one of the most valuable takeaways our students enjoy are learnings from their classmates, who represent a broad range of backgrounds, companies and industries," says Julie Cisek Jones, assistant dean and director of the Kellogg School of Management's EMBA programmes. "Single-company EMBA programmes lack the benefits a truly diverse student body can bring."\par \par \uc2 David Ardis, EMBA programme director at the University of Michigan's Stephen M. Ross School of Business, points out the benefits of having, for example, students from the non-profit sector alongside participants from the business world.\par \par \uc2 "You see the non-profit students challenge the corporate-sponsored candidates on issues such as \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and that is exactly the kind of exchange we want to happen," he says.\par \par \uc2 This can work both ways, as Pat Auger, EMBA programme director at Melbourne Business School in Australia, notes, "People from the non-profit sector learn to speak the language of the corporate sector," he says. "That helps when they go back to work in terms of their relationship with the commercial world. It's a win-win for both sides."\par \par \uc2 MBS's latest intake of 39 people includes an Australian police chief and a doctor, Australia-born but working in Switzerland for a big pharmaceutical company. Prof Auger does not see his school getting into a single-company programme, and says that, if it was approached to run one, he would at least try to argue the merits of a consortium degree, involving two to four companies, achieving some diversity in the classroom.\par \par \uc2 Even the consortium approach, however, can outlive its usefulness. At Ashridge Business School in the UK, the last cohort in a consortium programme involving four German companies finishes its work this year and graduates next May. The programme ran for 12 years and was considered an ideal "halfway house" between the single company EMBA and a standard open programme.\par \par \uc2 With Lufthansa, Deutsche Bank, Merck KGaA and Robert Bosch as the partners, participants came from several countries, including Germany.\par \par \uc2 Even so, says Steve Seymour, director of the school's part-time EMBA, "there was a view, among the participants and at Ashridge, that there needed to be more breadth and exposure to a wider group". A consortium may work, he says, but as business is increasingly global, it was felt that having four German companies in the consortium was not the best idea for the future.\par \par \uc2 All four companies are still working with Ashridge, whether sending students on the open EMBA or doing other things, says Dr Seymour.\par \par \uc2 The school's latest EMBA has 36 people in 12 nationalities, all from different companies. "The more diverse the group is, the better it works," he says.\par \par \uc2 Depending on the company's objectives for its single-company programme, however, it may not be relevant or necessary to have participants from other companies involved.\par \par \uc2 The Danfoss programme at Henley, for example, aims to bring employees in from around the world and build a Danfoss community, says Prof Bones.\par \par \uc2 Ms Vanstraelen, meanwhile, insists IBM is such a broad church that it can achieve all the diversity it needs to ensure participants can benefit from each others' varied careers and experiences.\par \par \uc2 With activities ranging from consulting to software, and with staff functions such as human resources and finance participating alongside the business units, there is, she says, "probably more diversity than in 50 per cent of open programmes".\par \par \uc2 ....................................................\par \par \uc2 IBM move was a key stroke\par \par \uc2 At 27, Nina Rasmussen is the youngest in her cohort on IBM's single-company EMBA programme, run by Warwick Business School in the UK. She has yet to finish the course - her dissertation is the main task outstanding - but it is already having an impact on her career at IBM.\par \par \uc2 This May, Ms Rasmussen switched to a sales job, and is now a general business client representative at IBM Denmark, working with several of the company's customers across the country.\par \par \uc2 "I really wanted sales experience, and it was partly as a result of doing the EMBA that I found out that it was very important," she says.\par \par \uc2 Having joined IBM Denmark as a trainee in 2000 and held a series of roles, Ms Rasmussen fits the company's criteria for joining the EMBA programme. "We expect people to have at least three years' experience and probably around five, to have a good understanding of IBM, to have delivered good results over the past two years and high talent, and we predict a bright future for them at IBM," says Mia Vanstraelen, director of human resources at IBM Benelux.\par \par \uc2 Critics of single-company programmes say it is harder to achieve the diversity in the cohort that contributes so much to the learning experience for individual students. But Ms Rasmussen says there is plenty of diversity on her programme - geographically, with students coming from all over Europe and Dubai, and from many different business units, as IBM is such a large company.\par \par \uc2 "I have met people from IBM's outsourcing side, who have very different roles from me, and the culture within those functions is different, too," she says. "It's just very interesting to learn about their jobs and what career opportunities there might be - it gives an insight into other areas of IBM that I could go to in the future."\par \par \uc2 She also appreciates a programme that is based mainly on e-learning, as it gives her the flexibility that IBM - along with other large companies - increasingly requires of its employees. "I can study when I like, and it can fit into my schedule," she says.\par \par \uc2 The programme involves an average of about eight extra hours a week, she says, and workshops are held three or four times a year, at Warwick or elsewhere in Europe. There is a lot of group work, says Ms Rasmussen, so it helps to be able to meet fellow students face-to-face periodically.\par \par \uc2 She stresses that the programme has a broad academic agenda and does not look inwardly at IBM. "When we are being taught, the subjects are not really focused on IBM but on the general business world, taking information from different companies all over the world," she says.\par \par \uc2 Being assigned a mentor, who has also done an MBA, has helped Ms Rasmussen see how she can relate the qualification to her future career development. "I have a clear plan and goals for where I want to go," she says, "and [doing the EMBA] has definitely helped me move forward."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20081027_19702_20.xml\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gedu : \uc2 Education | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News\cell \pard