ha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 It is easy to imagine \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  being the first fad that companies abandon during the downturn,\par \par \uc2 With businesses struggling, how many companies will fret about organic cotton T-shirts or how much workers earn in faraway factories? How many consumers, short of cash and worried about losing their jobs, will bother to ask?\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The disappearance of corporate responsibility seems a plausible prediction - except that one company last week pledged to continue taking it seriously. And because that company is \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2 , the world's most powerful retailer, thousands of other companies will be forced to take it seriously, too.\par \par \uc2 Lee Scott, \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2 's chief executive, told a meeting of 1,000 Chinese suppliers in Beijing: "I firmly believe that a company that cheats on overtime and on the age of its labour, that dumps its scraps and its chemicals in our rivers, that does not pay its taxes or honour its contracts, will ultimately cheat on the quality of its products."\par \par \uc2 Mr Scott accepted his timing might look odd. "Some may wonder, even inside \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2 , with all that is going on in the global economy, should being a socially and environmentally responsible company still be a priority? You're darn right sustainability should be a priority."\par \par \uc2 Hearing \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  say this still produces splutters of disbelief. This is the company that campaigners have accused of mistreating its employees at home, driving down wages abroad and ruining the landscape with its giant, out-of-town stores. But Mr Scott has been talking this way since 2005, when he promised \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  would "sell products that sustain our resources and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ".\par \par \uc2 In Beijing last week, Mike Duke, vice-chairman of \uc2 Wal-Mart Stores\uc2 , told the Chinese suppliers to expect random inspection of their factories. They would have to hand over the location of every factory they used.\par \par \uc2 "It will mean that if you sell us tennis shoes, we expect you to know - and we expect you to tell us - not just where the tennis shoes were assembled, but which subcontractors played a role in making them. And if there is an issue with those shoes, we expect you to have the answers," Mr Duke said.\par \par \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  would begin demanding Chinese suppliers to stores in the US, UK and Canada sign up to rigorous environmental and social standards in three months. Within three years, all suppliers to \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  stores anywhere in the world would have to sign up.\par \par \uc2 It would not just be about factory conditions. Suppliers would be judged on their air emissions and hazardous waste disposal.\par \par \uc2 Why is \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  doing this? There are, no doubt, political reasons. The US seems poised to elect a president who has been no friend of the company's practices. In a debate during the Democratic presidential primaries, Barack Obama thought there was mileage in reminding Hillary Clinton that from 1986 to 1992 she was "a corporate lawyer sitting on the board at \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2 ".\par \par \uc2 The company also knows consumer activists will continue to target it, recession or not. Companies cannot bury controversy in the age of YouTube, social networks and bloggers, Mr Duke told the suppliers.\par \par \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  Watch, a campaigning group, dismissed the Beijing gathering, saying it did not address "the real problem: \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2 's infamous push for the lowest costs possible, no matter what".\par \par \uc2 This is a fair point. \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  has made its fortune offering customers the lowest prices. Mr Scott told the suppliers that customers were looking for quality, too - " people want a sock that will not fall down" - but he accepted that "working men and women everywhere are feeling pinched. They do not just want low prices right now. They need low prices."\par \par \uc2 So how is \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  planning to marry improved factory practices with dirt-cheap products? \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  does not actually talk much about corporate responsibility. Its phrase, following recent corporate fashion, is "sustainability". It has proved to be a sophisticated way to cut costs.\par \par \uc2 Sustainability involves reducing the amount of energy used in production and the amount of waste thrown away. Getting rid of unnecessary packaging also helps.\par \par \uc2 The company also told its suppliers it wanted to reduce defective products so they were "virtually out of existence" by 2012. This is an echo of the quality management movement that began in Japan after the second world war, which preached that doing things right first time, rather than correcting mistakes, reduced costs, too.\par \par \uc2 But paying workers their overtime is more expensive than not paying it. Suppliers will be hard pressed to provide \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  with the products it wants at the price it demands - reduced energy inputs or not. Many will struggle.\par \par \uc2 However, last week \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2  laid out the standard by which others will judge it. At a time of such uncertainty, that is a bold move.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20081027_19702_391.xml\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c42 : \uc2 Labor/Personnel Issues | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfcpin : \uc2 FC&E Industry News Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IPC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 CN\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trle