2 Andrew Baxter assesses the pros and cons of going it alone\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Open EMBA programmes may be in the majority, but single-company courses retain their supporters - and may be the better option in certain cases.\par \par \uc2 "The great big, behemoth [single-company] programmes are probably on the way out," says Chris Bones, dean of Henley Business School at the University of Reading, in the UK. "Sheep-dipping large numbers of people through a reasonably generic qualification is not, I think, the best investment you can make if you are going to do it without a purpose."\par \par \uc2 On the other hand, he says, there is always a role for development of talent on a single-company basis, whether it comes with a qualification attached, as with an EMBA or a more function-specific EMSc, or not, as in a short, tailored course of executive education.\par \par \uc2 The choice, says Prof Bones, is a strategic issue that will depend on the most important driver for the company: "Is this aligned to a strategic change in the organisation, so you want the programme to be very focused, tailored, and part of your competitive edge? Or is it part of a capability-building agenda where what you want to do is learn from and network with other people, and other sectors. They are two very different approaches, and both are right, at different times in an organisation's development."\par \par \uc2 Henley runs two single-company EMBA programmes, for Danfoss Group, the Danish manufacturer of mechanical and electronic products, and the medical division of \uc2 Johor Corporation\uc2 , a Malaysian conglomerate. Heads of agreement have just been signed with a third company, says Prof Bones.\par \par \uc2 Both Danfoss and Johor can fill a class that would ideally be 30-strong - enough to achieve high levels of interaction, he says. Being big enough to do that is a prerequisite for a single-company EMBA.\par \par \uc2 That is no problem for IBM, whose Europe-wide programme has been running for 12 years, moving in 2006 from Henley to Warwick Business School. IBM sends about 100 people on it each year, in two intakes.\par \par \uc2 Mia Vanstraelen, director of human resources at IBM Benelux, says IBM has tried an open programme in the past, working with a couple of other companies, but did not find it more beneficial.\par \par \uc2 "We invest in this type of programme because we really believe in fostering talent, and making sure our best employees have excellent opportunities to learn, while at the same time supporting the cultural and leadership changes which we are making at the company," she says.\par \par \uc2 Prof Bones says one main advantage of Henley's single-company EMBA is that the customer gets a huge opportunity to tailor cases, material and connectivity to its business, within a structure that is unchanged from the standard EMBA - thus retaining the same quality assurance that comes from accreditation and a high ranking.\par \par \uc2 The key drawback of single-company EMBA programmes, as viewed by schools that concentrate on the open version, is the perceived lack of diversity among the cohort.\par \par \uc2 "At the Kellogg School, one of the most valuable takeaways our students enjoy are learnings from their classmates, who represent a broad range of backgrounds, companies and industries," says Julie Cisek Jones, assistant dean and director of the Kellogg School of Management's EMBA programmes. "Single-company EMBA programmes lack the benefits a truly diverse student body can bring."\par \par \uc2 David Ardis, EMBA programme director at the University of Michigan's Stephen M. Ross School of Business, points out the benefits of having, for example, students from the non-profit sector alongside participants from the business world.\par \par \uc2 "You see the non-profit students challenge the corporate-sponsored candidates on issues such as \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and that is exactly the kind of exchange we want to happen," he says.\par \par \uc2 This can work both ways, as Pat Auger, EMBA programme director at Melbourne Business School in Australia, notes, "People from the non-profit sector learn to speak the language of the corporate sector," he says. "That helps when they go back to work in terms of their relationship with the commercial world. It's a win-win for both sides."\par \par \uc2 MBS's latest intake of 39 people includes an Australian police chief and a doctor, Australia-born but working in Switzerland for a big pharmaceutical company. Prof Auger does not see his school getting into a single-company programme, and says that, if it was approached to run one, he would at least try to argue the merits of a consortium degree, involving two to four companies, achieving some diversity in the classroom.\par \par \uc2 Even the consortium approach, however, can outlive its usefulness. At Ashridge Business School in the UK, the last cohort in a consortium programme involving four German companies finishes its work this year and graduates next May. The programme ran for 12 years and was considered an ideal "halfway house" between the single company EMBA and a standard open programme.\par \par \uc2 With Lufthansa, \uc2 Deutsche Bank\uc2 , \uc2 Merck KGaA\uc2  and Robert Bosch as the partners, participants came from several countries, including Germany.\par \par \uc2 Even so, says Steve Seymour, director of the school's part-time EMBA, "there was a view, among the participants and at Ashridge, that there needed to be more breadth and exposure to a wider group". A consortium may work, he says, but as business is increasingly global, it was felt that having four German companies in the consortium was not the best idea for the future.\par \par \uc2 All four companies are still working with Ashridge, whether sending students on the open EMBA or doing other things, says Dr Seymour.\par \par \uc2 The school's latest EMBA has 36 people in 12 nationalities, all from different companies. "The more diverse the group is, the better it works," he says.\par \par \uc2 Depending on the company's objectives for its single-company programme, however, it may not be relevant or necessary to have participants from other companies involved.\par \par \uc2 The Danfoss programme at Henley, for example, aims to bring employees in from around the world and build a Danfoss community, says Prof Bones.\par \par \uc2 Ms Vanstraelen, meanwhile, insists IBM is such a broad church that it can achieve all the diversity it needs to ensure participants can benefit from each others' varied careers and experiences.\par \par \uc2 With activities ranging from consulting to software, and with staff functions such as human resources and finance participating alongside the business units, there is, she says, "probably more diversity than in 50 per cent of open programmes".\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 ftnewspaper_20081027.xml|20081027S106.331\cell \pard \ql \li0\r