eting managers are looking for any edge they can get as they peddle products. \uc2 Harvard Business School professor John Quelch\uc2  suggests an unlikely weapon: \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  initiatives.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Quelch, co-author of "Greater Good: How Good Marketing Makes for Better Democracy" and a director at \uc2 Pepsi Bottling Group Inc\uc2 . and advertising company \uc2 WPP PLC\uc2 , contends in an interview that corporate social-good efforts can help companies emerge from the downturn stronger \u8211\'20\'13 with fiercer loyalty from both customers and employees. Edited excerpts follow:\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Spending on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  initiatives is a nice idea, but with the economy so lousy, how can a marketer realistically be expected to take social good into account?\par \par \uc2 Consumers pay a price premium for global brands in part because they expect those brands to deliver a higher level of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Companies that can afford to sustain their CSR initiatives will stand a better chance of cementing the loyalty of their consumers and come out of the downturn even stronger.\par \par \uc2 What are the consequences if a company cuts back on CSR efforts?\par \par \uc2 Consumers who have been attracted to the brand by a particular CSR initiative may well be disappointed if the company lapses. On the other hand, if the value delivered is adjusted for the downturn -- in other words if there's a price reduction or an increased level of promotion -- then the consumer may understand the tradeoff, forgive the brand [for cutting back on CSR] and look for the brand to get back on track when the economic cycle turns.\par \par \uc2 Can you give me a few examples of companies that have used CSR initiatives to gain an edge?\par \par \uc2 A longstanding example would be Timberland, which over the past 20 years has understood the social concerns of its target customers -- their appreciation of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , their appreciation of the need to give back to society. Timberland has a range of initiatives that both support employee social activity as well as address social challenges that are of relevance to its target consumers.\par \par \uc2 Another example, which is not a CSR initiative per se, is Dove. What Dove has done is focus on the problem of self-esteem around an individual teenager's ability to live up to media-created images of what constitutes real beauty.\par \par \uc2 A constant problem of managing large organizations is that senior executives can lay out lofty goals -- such as that from now on, brand managers need to consider social responsibility in their marketing practices \u8211\'20\'13 but the message doesn't necessarily get implemented by managers at the ground level. Why does this disconnect happen so often?\par \par \uc2 Actually [with CSR] I think the disconnect is often the other way around. The younger managers further down the organization would love to have the leadership embrace these issues to a greater degree than they do. Not walking the talk on the part of a CEO is a recipe for not merely failure, but also cynicism on the part of the rest of the organization. Younger managers, millennials in particular, really see it as their responsibility to make a difference in the world as part of their workplace activity.\par \par \uc2 How can CEOs better harness that enthusiasm among their young managers?\par \par \uc2 First, give permission to younger managers to explore how the values of the brand can be expressed through not just the physical functionality of the product or service, but through what it stands for and what it means to consumers. In addition there should be a mechanism whereby individuals from all levels and functions of the company can participate in truly important CSR initiatives that help to attract and retain top quality people. IBM for example has a tremendous track record in this area. They have an online community that enables current employees and retirees to provide advice to not-for-profit organizations.\par \par \uc2 Write to Erin White at {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "mailto:erin.white@wsj.com"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 erin.white@wsj.com }}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 pspbot : \uc2 The Pepsi Bottling Group Inc | wirp : \uc2 WPP PLC\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b IN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 i41 : \uc2 Food/Beverages/Tobacco | i428 : \uc2 Soft Drinks | i838 : \uc2 Advertising | iadv : \uc2 Advertisi