alpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Sleeping four to a tent in a military style bootcamp in Haiti is not every executive's idea of a useful or even entertaining way to spend their valuable time.\par \par \uc2 But for the past two years the Irish operation of Ernst & Young has taken a group of Ireland's most promising business people for a week's retreat to this poverty-stricken Caribbean island.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The initiative is part of the Irish Entrepreneur of the Year award, the local version of the global competition conducted by the business consultancy. Other such assemblies of contestants for business competitions are typically less challenging and more likely to involve golf or opera. But E&Y's Irish office set out to do something a bit different with its entrepreneurs.\par \par \uc2 "We wanted the contestants to be really challenged," says Enda Kelly, a former tax partner who runs what has become Ireland's best-known business award. "We wanted to bring them to an \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  they would really struggle in. Now these guys triumph in adversity - so we had to look for real adversity. So we went to Haiti, and by God did they meet adversity."\par \par \uc2 The trip is not strictly part of the competition, although the contestants did not seem aware of that. The idea was to see how they could harness their business skills in Haiti to help locals set up a number of projects such as reclaiming an irrigation dam and setting up an acquaculture venture. It sounds like the format for a reality TV show, as contestants are thrown into an unfamiliar foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 , in uncomfortably humid conditions, with few creature comforts.\par \par \uc2 Certainly, the strange choice of location did make an impression. "I'd been to the Dominican Republic for a family holiday, and that's the other half of the island and that was very poor but nothing to compare with Haiti," says Lord Kilclooney, owner of the Alpha Group of newspapers, former deputy leader of the Ulster Unionist party and, at 70, the oldest of the competitors.\par \par \uc2 Not only is Haiti one of the world's poorest countries, but it also suffers from endemic lawlessness such that the contestants had 24-hour armed guards wherever they went.\par \par \uc2 "We flew into Port au Prince. That was probably the most intimidating part of the journey. It just didn't look like the sort of place you might like to wander outside the airport," says Patricia O'Hagan, managing director of Core Systems, a Belfast software company.\par \par \uc2 "We were really out of our comfort zone," says David Bobbett, chief executive of Dublin-based H&K kitchen equipment company.\par \par \uc2 When Mr Kelly launched the Irish version of the competition in 1998, the main aim was to acclaim Irish business people, who he says were largely derided by the public and seen as "chancers" or untrustworthy. "We started as a typical awards programme, hauling people out as role models," he says. But by 2005 he had the idea to develop the programme during a trip to Harvard Business School with that year's contestants.\par \par \uc2 "It occurred to me that the academic we were all listening to imparted at most 20 per cent of the learning in that room. The rest came from the contributions of our entrepreneurs. What the academic did was he captured it. It was then I started looking at structuring our business awards programme to do the same."\par \par \uc2 On route for Haiti, Mr Kelly arranged for two days of seminars in Miami given by a noted expert on \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  - Kellie McElhaney, a professor at the Haas School of Business at Berkeley in California.\par \par \uc2 "When we were talking to Kellie about the trip, she had never heard anything so daft in her life. But she came down to Haiti too. In fact, she only charged us for the two days in the classroom," says Mr Kelly.\par \par \uc2 Dragging busy people away from the demands of their businesses is a task. E&Y encouraged contestants leave their laptops behind, though mobile phones were allowed for essential calls.\par \par \uc2 But in spite of the occasional distraction of business demands back home, all agreed the experience of a week in Haiti forced contestants to think about their own businesses in a new light.\par \par \uc2 "As an entrepreneur you can get a bit myopic and focus on the ground all the time, not on the horizon. Working with other people who are completely outside your purview was very exciting," says Terence Brannigan, head of Resource, a contract cleaning and other soft services company.\par \par \uc2 The contestants not only left something behind but also learnt to work together, they say. Typically entrepreneurs are big on self-belief, but are not always good team players. Sean Roland, president of Hibernia College, an e-learning company, says: "I was expecting a lot of preening of feathers but that was all left at home in Ireland."\par \par \uc2 Johnny Flaherty, of C&F, a Galway toolmaker and overall winner of the awards finals announced at the end of October, says: "If you could get a workforce to work the way this group of entrepreneurs did for this week in Haiti, it would be a fantastic company."\par \par \uc2 And between the contestants, alliances have been forged that would not have happened in the normal course of business - or in a few rounds of golf. "I have got so much business out of the trip, business I wouldn't have even thought of targeting," says James Kilbane, chairman of Grafton Recruiting, a Dublin-based recruitment company.\par \par \uc2 "Entrepreneurs are often great communicators. They know their customers. They know their suppliers and their advisers but they often haven't met many other entrepreneurs. Now they will each know about 100 entrepreneurs. Many of them say it is the best network they have," says Mr Kelly.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20081209_4930_498.xml\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 csmlbs : \uc2 Small Business/Entrepreneurs | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Fact