lpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Water could not be more vital to achieving economic development.\par \par \uc2 Without easy access to clean water and sanitation, people face extreme hardship - more than 5,000 children die every day in the developing world from preventable diseases such as diarrhoea, water-borne or caused by poor hygiene. A lack of sanitation is probably the single biggest killer in the world, according to poverty campaigners.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The other problems caused by this lack may be less severe, but still crippling to progress: the days of sickness preventing people from working, the waste of time - and sometimes the danger - involved in fetching water from far away, the high prices paid to street water sellers for poor quality water. Some of the consequences are less obvious: girls in Africa, for instance, often stop going to school when they reach puberty if there are no toilets to give them privacy.\par \par \uc2 "Water is critical - it is the first thing you need for economic development," says Miguel Jurado, vice-president and head of international markets at Aqualia, a Spanish water company. "First you need clean water, then energy, then transport and telecommunications. These are the basics for development."\par \par \uc2 The United Nations University, in a recent study, said water and sanitation should be the main focus for development aid, as without them, efforts to improve education, health and trade flounder. "Development aid would be much better spent if you tackled the water and sanitation issue first," says Zafar Adeel, director of the university's international network on water, \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and health. What good is a school if the pupils are frequently too sick to attend lessons, or miss classes because they have to walk miles to carry water home?\par \par \uc2 As water and sanitation are so fundamental to human progress, any investment in improving these services pays high dividends. The UN estimates that $1 spent on water and sanitation in developing countries produces $8 to $10 in return in economic development.\par \par \uc2 Yet the investments needed in this most fundamental infrastructure are not being made.\par \par \uc2 In fact, rich countries are giving a smaller proportion of their aid budgets to water and sanitation than in the past, according to a recent report by the charities Tearfund and WaterAid. Furthermore, what aid they are giving is all too often focused on the regions that need it least, such as China and the Middle East rather than Africa, where the problem is most severe.\par \par \uc2 Another problem is that sanitation attracts much less attention than water. The Millennium Development Goals, for instance, which were set up by the UN to try to solve some of the most critical problems in poor nations, call for the number of people without access to clean water to be halved, but have no explicit goal on sanitation - despite the fact that 2.6bn people lack access to decent sanitation, and its lack is a major factor keeping them in poverty.\par \par \uc2 "It's unsexy," says Vicky Cann, policy officer at the World Development Movement, a campaigning group. "Sanitation is not glamorous. It's something that people don't want to talk about - there are lot of taboos there. And this is reflected in [rich countries'] political priorities [in their aid budgets]."\par \par \uc2 As a result, she says, progress on sanitation is "far too slow". This inaction is holding back poor countries severely.\par \par \uc2 What can the private sector do to improve access to water and sanitation, and thus economic development, in poor countries?\par \par \uc2 Some companies, particularly those in the food and drink sector or those with water-related technologies, have chosen \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  projects focusing on helping people in poor nations to gain access to the sort of services that rich countries take for granted.\par \par \uc2 For instance, Diageo runs a Water for Life project in developing countries, which will have brought water services to 2m people by the end of this financial year. \uc2 Coca-Cola\uc2  and Pepsi also run water initiatives, as do companies such as \uc2 Procter & Gamble\uc2 , which has a water-filter technology called Pur that it donates to some projects and sells at a low cost to others, and \uc2 Dow Chemical\uc2 , which provides water technology free or at low cost in projects in India, Africa, central America and the Caribbean.\par \par \uc2 Water companies should also see the opportunity for providing water and sanitation in poor areas, says Mr Jurado: "The participation of private companies only needs a reasonably secure legal framework which guarantees a return on the big investments that are needed."\par \par \uc2 There are difficulties, though, says Antoine Fr\u233\'00\'E9rot, chief executive of \uc2 Veolia\uc2  Water. Politicians must put the right framework in place to enable companies to provide services.\par \par \uc2 And Ms Cann warns that some rich countries have taken the idea of private provision in developing countries too far, by assuming that water and sanitation services can be provided privately and therefore cutting their aid. This, she says, leaves "a black hole in funding" for water projects.\par \par \uc2 Poor people are willing to pay for water and sanitation - in many developing countries, they pay many times more per litre than the rich for their water, as they have to buy it by the canister from street vendors. But in many parts of the world they have been poorly served by the public sector and private sector alike.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20081215_13196_328.xml\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gdev : \uc2 Development/Humanitarian Aid | gpov : \uc2 Poverty | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gcom : \uc2 Society/Community/Work | gdip : \uc2 International Relations | gpir : \uc2 Politics/International Relations | gsoc : \uc2 Social Issues\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertal