ay with an apology: he was no Warren Buffett. There would be no pithy phrases, no quoting of Mae West's "I was Snow White but I drifted".\par \par \uc2 Instead there was Mr Gates' passion for eradicating polio, finding a gel to prevent HIV infection and raising US high school standards.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 In his letter from the Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation, he also championed an idea he called "creative capitalism". As Mr Gates said, he is no phrase-maker.\par \par \uc2 There is already another dull term, \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , that has been around for longer. Newer manifestations of CSR, such as Professor C.K. Prahalad's "fortune at the bottom of the pyramid" have more zing.\par \par \uc2 Prof Prahalad's phrase also captured an innovative idea - that companies could make money selling to the poorest - while creative capitalism is a rehash of many old ones.\par \par \uc2 First proposed by Mr Gates at last year's World Economic Forum in Davos, Creative Capitalism is now the title of a book, reviewed in the Financial Times last week.\par \par \uc2 The book starts with Mr Gates' views on what businesses, philanthropists and governments should be doing about poverty and illness. It continues with a series of responses, many from US academics, who generally give the \uc2 Microsoft\uc2  founder a good kicking for his allegedly sloppy thinking.\par \par \uc2 Central to the Gates view is that, while capitalism has been a tremendous force for good, its benefits do not reach the very poor. "Diseases like malaria that kill over a million people a year get far less attention than drugs to help with baldness," Mr Gates said.\par \par \uc2 Mr Gates, who has stepped down from day-to-day \uc2 Microsoft\uc2  management, argues we need to create incentives to encourage businesses to join governments and philanthropists in helping the poor. He adds that where it is not possible to make profits from serving the needy, companies should enjoy the recognition that comes from doing good. His critics lay into him, many quoting Milton Friedman's view that corporate executives' sole job is "to make as much money as possible while conforming to the basic rules of the society" and that, if they want to support other causes, they should do it with their own cash and in their own time.\par \par \uc2 The criticism does not come only from the political right. Lawrence Summers, now a leading member of President Barack Obama's US administration, argues that \uc2 Fannie Mae\uc2  and \uc2 Freddie Mac\uc2  provide proof of what goes wrong when companies become confused about whether to make profits or serve society. "When there were social failures, the companies always blamed their need to perform for their shareholders. When there were business failures, it was always the result of their social obligations," Mr Summers writes.\par \par \uc2 Others argue that the best way to help the world's poor is to bring capitalism to them, along with good governance and less corruption.\par \par \uc2 There is force to these views, but none explains why CSR refuses to die under the heat of its opponents' unremitting logic. Indeed, it is winning new and surprising adherents.\par \par \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2 , favourite target of anti-corporate campaigners, told a meeting of Chinese suppliers last year that it would not deal with them if they employed underage workers or polluted rivers. The company added that it would continue to encourage suppliers to cut down on packaging, thereby both reducing costs and helping the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Why do companies persist in behaving this way? Partly because they see business benefits. Having to answer constant criticism about sweatshop conditions takes up management time. Bad publicity demoralises employees and dissuades new recruits from joining. This may matter less during the period of high unemployment we are entering when recruits may be happy to find a job at all. Cutting down waste, on the other hand, which companies now call "sustainability", will probably grow during the recession.\par \par \uc2 But I suspect there is more to executives' stubborn adherence to social responsibility: it makes them feel better. Many retiring capitalists say they want to "give something back". The critics would argue that building successful companies and creating jobs is contribution enough.\par \par \uc2 Many clearly feel it is not. Mr Gates is one of a long line of company creators to turn to philanthropy. Repentant atheists sometimes say they felt a "God-sized hole" in their lives. Mr Gates clearly felt a Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation-sized hole in his life.\par \par \uc2 It is his money and he can do what he wants with it. Few can afford to turn their backs on full-time work as young as Mr Gates did. Not having his wealth, they use their companies' instead. That may sully what the critics see as companies' only proper objective but, as vital as profit is, it seems insufficient to give people the fulfilment they crave.\par \par \uc2 michael.skapinker@ft.com\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin