hlight\uc2  and reducing poverty are linked - and non-profits must adapt accordingly, says Sarah Murray\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Eight years ago, the natural habitat of the Hail Haor wetland on the eastern shores of northern Bangladesh was in a poor state, with aquatic plants dying and fish and wildfowl dis-appearing.\par \par \uc2 Since then, a programme granting fishing rights to locals and training them in fisheries management has reversed the decline. But it is not only the natural \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  that has benefited. Locals are enjoying a 140 per cent increase in fish catches and a 33 per cent rise in their incomes.\par \par \uc2 The success of the project, which was funded by the US Agency for International Development, demonstrates how protecting the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and reducing poverty are inextricably linked. But if the philanthropic sector is to achieve similar results, the question is whether organisations can broaden their remit sufficiently and attract funding for programmes focused on issues that were once the preserve of others.\par \par \uc2 Many senior government and philanthropy leaders are making the correlation between human development and climate change.\par \par \uc2 It has, for example, long been recognised that funding girls' education has a high social return. But some now argue that it could also be good for the planet. Bill Clinton, former US president, says that if the world is to meet tough emissionsreduction targets, population growth must also be addressed.\par \par \uc2 "The only thing you see across every region of the world - across every culture, across all religious groups - that always works is to put all the girls in school and give all the young women access to the labour market," says Mr Clinton, whose Clinton Global Initiative convenes some of the world's biggest givers. "There is no culture in which that has not succeeded in lowering the birth rate - because women want to have their own lives as well as to bear children."\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Barack Obama, the US president, has argued that investing in solar and wind power and other forms of renewable energy could be a way not only to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and promote energy independence, but also to help create jobs in green or environmentrelated industries.\par \par \uc2 In the philanthropic world, aid workers operating on the ground have long seen these kinds of connections in action. However, at a strategic level, the tendency for many charities and nongovernmental organisations has been to fall into one camp or the other, particularly when it comes to environmental conservation.\par \par \uc2 "Rather than looking at how to invest in nature for development, for many years the core strategy of environmental groups was to promote protected areas at all costs, which is very polarising," says Janet Ranganathan, head of science and research at the World Resources Institute and lead author of a new WRI book* designed to help decision makers link ecosystems and economic development.\par \par \uc2 Fundraising pressures have also led many organisations to concentrate their efforts on addressing single issues rather than expanding their horizons to include broader activities.\par \par \uc2 "The reality is that there's not an unlimited pool of philanthropic dollars in the world," says Brian Richter, director of the Nature Conservancy's Global Freshwater Programme. "And that simple scarcity of money to support non-profits breeds competition among organisations that was problematic in past years and continues to be an issue."\par \par \uc2 When it comes to donors, this could be exacerbated by the global economic downturn and its impact on giving. "Donors are pulling back a bit and staying with their core commitments," says Mark Kramer, founder and managing director of FSG Social Impact Advisors. "They are less likely to try new ways of tackling these problems and may pull back from anything new - so it could actually discourage this approach."\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, as the growing connections between the world's problems emerges, large, progressive global non-profits and charities have recognised that protecting the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and fostering economic development are not necessarily conflicting aims.\par \par \uc2 For Oxfam - the charity whose mission is to fight poverty and injustice around the world - combating climate change is now most prominent among its campaigns. Oxfam says the effects of unpredictable weather patterns are likely to hurt the world's poorest people the most.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the World Wildlife Fund - which was established to protect endangered species and prevent the degradation of the natural \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  - is working to place the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  at the heart of economic development and demonstrate the importance of poverty reduction to conservation.\par \par \uc2 Mr Kramer says that forward-thinking funders, too, are adapting their strategies. "We see a shift broadly in the way the most prominent leaders of philanthropy are approaching philanthropy - which is thinking more about what are the tools to solve a problem rather than which charity to write a cheque to," he says.\par \par \uc2 Yet the philanthropic sector still includes a vast number of organisations for whom a single mission - whether it is saving the panda or feeding motherless children - dominates the agenda.\par \par \uc2 "The reason that child is motherless is because they have been kicked off their land, the water quality has failed or there has been a flood because a forest has been cut down," says Ms Ranganathan. "That's a more complicated message."\par \par \uc2 And a complicated message can make fundraising more difficult, particularly for the many non-profits that have traditionally motivated donors and grassroots supporters by appealing to their passion for a single issue.\par \par \uc2 "Silos are created because often that is the way one can get funding and get programme-specific support," says Chris Deri, head of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  and sustainability at Edelman, the global communications firm. "So sometimes it is difficult for individual or institutional funders to connect all the dots in their funding."\par \par \uc2 For charitable organisations, the challenge is to adapt the messages that they put out to their donors. "For the last 30 years, NGOs have perpetrated a singleissue approach to these things," says Mr Deri. "So we're fighting against out own rhetoric."\par \par \uc2 Joining the dots may be easier for organisations that, from the outset, have specialised in missions in which the lines between conservation and poverty alleviation are blurred. One example is E+Co, a non-profit that funds clean energy enterprises in developing countries as a means of both tackling climate change and poverty and uses 34 social, environmental and financial indicators to calculate the return on its investments.\par \par \uc2 "It takes a special skill-set and point of view to understand how to address the environmental and development together," says Mr Kramer. "So there is a specialised set of organisations that have emerged in the past few years that have the expertise to address these issues together."\par \par \uc2 Another way for nonprofits to broaden their mission is by forming alliances with other organisations that have different but complementary expertise. This is the approach being taken by the Nature Conservancy. Its Alliance for Water Stewardship is an initiative that includes a range of partners, from other non-profits to businesses and governments.\par \par \uc2 "Our forte is in the environmental aspects of water use," says Mr Richter. "So we have sought out other partners that have expertise in the development and social issues."\par \par \uc2 He believes that the trend towards multi-issue partnerships will increase as the complexity of dealing with the world's problems becomes more apparent. "No one organisation is going to be fully capable of addressing all these concerns," he says. "And you can build strength through these alliances and access different areas of expertise."\par \par \uc2 Whether it will be through alliances between donors and non-profits or the emergence of specialised organisations, the pressure for the philanthropic community to address environmental issues and poverty together is increasing. Part of the reason is that the effects of ecosystem degradation and climate change are starting to be felt. Most prominently, the global food crisis has highlighted the fact that climate changes are likely to have a direct impact on the ability of poor nations to feed their populations.\par \par \uc2 Ms Ranganathan believes the most powerful tool in forming a bridge between the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  and development will therefore be the concept of "ecosystems services".\par \par \uc2 "By focusing on dependencies [of humans on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 ], we will inherently start reconciling these two traditionally siloed groups," she says. "Because if we're going to make a compelling argument for saving ecosystems, it's not the argument of saving them for nature's sake, but saving them for people's sake."\par \par \uc2 * Ecosystem Services: 