ustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (Copyright (c) 2009, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.) \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 When companies set up shop in developing countries, they often find that they have to do a lot more than just run a business.\par \par \uc2 In many of these countries, local institutions can't meet basic needs, from health care and education to roads and reliable electricity. But companies can't operate without a healthy, productive work force and solid infrastructure -- so, more and more of them are taking matters into their own hands. Companies are laying down roads and water pipes, setting up schools and hospitals and bankrolling a range of social programs.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 In other words, companies increasingly are taking on functions typically handled by the public sector.\par \par \uc2 This new role, however, isn't easy. Companies are struggling to figure out how to help locals without making them too dependent, while also finding ways to placate shareholders back home who may not see the value of all these pricey investments.\par \par \uc2 Even companies that go into emerging markets specifically to provide public services may end up in a maze of complications. For instance, utilities that open in a newly deregulated country often must play politics to win over activists who consider them interlopers.\par \par \uc2 What follows is a guide for companies that are starting operations in emerging markets. We'll look at the four basic approaches companies take to providing social services, as well as the challenges each strategy presents -- and the best ways to overcome them.\par \par \uc2 Into the Breach\par \par \uc2 In the first approach, companies directly take on public-service roles, even when these have little relationship to their core business. For instance, a mining company might build schools, health-care facilities or general infrastructure -- things that have nothing to do with the job of mining but are essential to creating an \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  for doing business.\par \par \uc2 Consider Magadi Soda Co. When the mining company -- a part of India's \uc2 TATA Chemicals Ltd\uc2 . -- set up operations in Kenya, it discovered that almost all government-funded public programs in the region were centered on the city of Nairobi. But the company was outside city limits -- and lacked the infrastructure it needed for its operations.\par \par \uc2 So, Magadi Soda started building. It extended the 75-mile road from the southern edges of Nairobi to the company's facilities in Lake Magadi, and built and operated an extension of the Kenyan railway line to transport soda ash to the port of Mombasa. It also introduced a passenger coach to offer transport services to the public along the route.\par \par \uc2 The road and railway are now used by Kenyans with little relationship to the company, and the company helps the community maintain rural access roads.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Magadi Soda bolstered its work force by ensuring the health and safety of local residents. The company constructed water-treatment plants and extended water distribution to surrounding communities. It also built up local housing, health care and education facilities, as well as supporting other local schools and providing scholarships for students.\par \par \uc2 But taking on a big public role carries risks. For one thing, activists may derail well-meaning programs by questioning why companies are acting like governments -- with few, if any, measures in place to ensure accountability. Then there's the question of creating dependency among local communities. Once made, public commitments may escalate and be difficult to reverse. Companies can face a backlash if they retrench investments because of difficult financial times, or pressure from shareholders or a parent firm.\par \par \uc2 One way to avoid these concerns is to take on a sweeping role only when the lack of public services represents an immediate threat to the surrounding community or the company, such as a famine or drought. In fact, that's the strategy some big companies favor in developing countries. Still, even if companies aren't planning long-term social efforts, just emergency relief, they should keep community concerns in mind and involve locals in decision making as early as possible.\par \par \uc2 Working Through Others\par \par \uc2 Another solution to the problems encountered above is to rely on other organizations to provide necessary services.\par \par \uc2 With this approach, companies help establish local groups, or bolster existing ones, that make decisions about public welfare and implement social programs. These groups take on the responsibility and accountability for providing necessities, leaving the company in a purely support role, such as providing funds. This might not be an answer to immediate problems -- such as helping a community deal with drought -- but it can build up long-term capabilities, so communities can eventually handle crises themselves.\par \par \uc2 That's what Magadi Soda ended up doing. The company eventually became uncomfortable with the government-like role it was playing. So, senior executives helped set up a county council and brought the local community on board to prioritize the company's public programs. This reduced the company's costs and minimized its obligation to operate activities in which it had little expertise.\par \par \uc2 Or consider a Russian aluminum producer that found itself facing a host of problems in the communities where it operated. Pressure was on to hire and source supplies locally. But public health and education were deteriorating -- hurting the potential work force -- and there were few small businesses to draw on.\par \par \uc2 The company decided to help the communities help themselves. It organized nongovernmental organizations, or NGOs, and community foundations in and around the regions it operated, and then provided funding for critical programs. The result? The groups partnered with local communities to launch educational and health-care facilities, and nurture small businesses that ended up in the company's supply chain.\par \par \uc2 Again, though, companies that adopt this approach face a number of challenges. Unlike the strategy Magadi Soda used at first, which brings immediate results, this approach requires a longer-term investment of resources. And that can lead to grumbling from shareholders back home or local communities in need.\par \par \uc2 What's more, companies must be careful to build good relationships in the community. If they don't take the time to learn local concerns, they may end up fostering groups and programs that don't really address what communities need, potentially leading to friction.\par \par \uc2 To ease pressure for immediate results, a company should work hard to educate shareholders and locals on its goals, stressing the long-term payoff and downplaying short-term benchmarks. As for strengthening local relationships, company officials must commit to spending time in the community. In our research in Africa, for instance, CEOs commented on the importance of regularly visiting communities and senior chiefs to gain sensitivity to their ways of life.\par \par \uc2 Core Concern\par \par \uc2 In the next approach, companies once again take over direct delivery of public services. But there's an important difference: Here, they're doing it as part of their core business.\par \par \uc2 In these cases, companies are moving into emerging markets precisely because the markets lack basic necessities; the companies see a chance to make a profit by filling the void. Utilities, for instance, often move into newly deregulated markets, while security firms enter regions racked by violence.\par \par \uc2 Companies taking this route may not want to engage in politics, but they often find themselves enmeshed in it anyway. Local communities often put up fierce resistance to the idea of putting basic necessities such as food, water and safety in the hands of a for-profit operation.\par \par \uc2 That's not the only challenge these companies face. It may be tough even for a well-intentioned company to remain committed to the interests of the community it serves. Eventually, shareholders or management may pressure the company to make moves that are good for business but bad for locals, such as eliminating crucial services.\par \par \uc2 One strategy to build local confidence and stay focused on serving the community: hire area residents to do as many jobs as possible, even if it means helping them get up to speed.\par \par \uc2 For instance, an African eco-tourism company was taking steps to maintain the ecosystems around its game reserves. The broad effort involved educating local communities and building up their infrastructure so they wouldn't need to cut trees for fuel or poach wildlife for food. To help win trust, the company worked with communities to develop a security force at the reserves, instead of bringing in its own private service.\par \par \uc2 From the Ground Up\par \par \uc2 The final strategy involves building up local institutions that help provide crucial services, much as the Russian company did. But, in this case, delivering those services is integral to the company's core business -- not just something it needs to do to run its operations smoothly.\par \par \uc2 Consider Sekem, an Egyptian company that promotes sustainable development. Among other efforts, the company sells locally grown organic produce in international markets. To further its goals, the company helped create the Egyptian Biodynamic Association, a nongovernmental organization that promotes the organic-agriculture movement among the country's farmers and provides them with research and training.\par \par \uc2 As ever, there are important challenges to consider. Mostly, they arise because of the type of companies that use this method -- generally, start-ups without deep resources to draw on. Companies that use the other strategies are usually much larger, with considerable funds to invest in social programs. And there's greater precedent for large companies to provide or sponsor social services. Start-ups don't have the same name recognition or authority, and must work harder to win the trust of locals, investors and agencies.\par \par \uc2 One thing that can help these companies is flexibility. Given their often-limited resources, companies must be prepared to scale back plans that prove unworkable. One entrepreneur, for instance, wanted to create a bank for people in emerging markets, to give them greater access to credit. But as he researched the idea, he realized that most people in the developing world simply wouldn't be able to qualify for loans under traditional lending standards.\par \par \uc2 So, he scrapped his original plan and came up with an alternative approach. He created a bank that gave out "microloans," often just a few dollars each. The loans were much easier to qualify for and pay back -- making them a much better fit for the developing world.\par \par \uc2 ---\par \par \uc2 Dr. Valente is an assistant professor of strategic management and business sustainability at the University of Victoria's Faculty of Business in Victoria, British Columbia. Dr. Crane is the George R. Gardiner professor of business ethics and director of the Erivan K. Haub Program in Business and Sustainability at York University's Schulich School of Business in Toronto. They can be reached at reports@wsj.com.\par \par \uc2 ---\par \par \uc2 For Further Reading\par \par \uc2 These related articles from MIT Sloan Management Review can be accessed online at sloanreview.mit.edu/wsj\par \par \uc2 The High Impact of Collaborative Social Initiatives\par \par \uc2 By John A. Pearce II and Jonathan P. Doh (Spring 2005)\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  has become a vital part of the business conversation.\par \par \uc2 Creating Sustainable Local Enterprise Networks\par \par \uc2 By David Wheeler, Kevin McKague, Jane Thomson, Rachel Davies, Jacqueline Medalye and Marina Prada (Fall 2005)\par \par \uc2 In developing countries, examples of successful sustainable enterprise often involve informal networks that include businesses, not-for-profit organizations and communities.\par \par \uc2 The Great Leap: Driving Innovation From the Base of the Pyramid\par \par \uc2 By Stuart L. Hart and Clayton M. Christensen (Fall 2002)\par \par \uc2 Billions of poor people aspire to join the world's economy. Disruptive innovation can pave the way, helping companies combine sustainable corporate growth with social responsibility.\par \par \uc2 How to Win in Emerging Markets\par \par \uc2 By Satish Shankar, Charles Ormiston, Nicolas Bloch, Robert Schaus and Vijay Vishwanath (Spring 2008)\par \par \uc2 Though competitive barriers in Asia, Latin America and Eastern Europe are many, a look at the companies that are thriving there reveals some secrets that make success more likely.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.djreprints.com/link/DJRFactiva.html?FACTIVA=wjco20090323000079"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 License this article from Dow Jones Reprint Service}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RE\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 usa : \uc2 United States | namz : \uc2 North America\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \tro