um\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (Copyright (c) 2009, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.) \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The bad economy and a fundamental shift in the market for luxury goods are forcing an industry that reveres names like Chanel and Versace to embrace a different icon: Mother Nature.\par \par \uc2 Over the past year, many of the world's best-known luxury labels have started to introduce ecofriendly products, snap up brands that tout their social responsibility and weave environmental themes into their advertising and marketing. In May, French luxury conglomerate \uc2 LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton\uc2  took a stake in Edun, an organic-clothing company founded by the singer Bono and his wife.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Other companies have begun to advertise steps they took years ago to promote resource conservation. This summer, the windows of \uc2 Tiffany &Co\uc2 .'s retail stores world-wide feature images of coral reefs, publicizing Tiffany's commitment since 2002 not to use coral in its designs.\par \par \uc2 "We want to change the way we conceive our business, socially and environmentally speaking," said Francois-Henri Pinault, chief executive of French retail giant \uc2 PPR SA\uc2 , which has sponsored a feature-length documentary film highlighting man's abuse of the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The film, which was released in 131 countries last month, was produced by French director Luc Besson but PPR's hand in it is clear: In the film's opening credits the company's brand names -- Gucci, Yves Saint Laurent, Bottega Veneta and others -- swirl around and coalesce into the film's title, "Home."\par \par \uc2 The luxury industry's adoption of a green message reflects the challenges facing some of the world's most glamorous brands. Once able to win customers with the promise of fine design, craftsmanship and service, the luxury business is contending with an aging core clientele and the aftermath of a decade-long expansion that has rendered exclusive brands less so than they used to be.\par \par \uc2 Those factors have purveyors of high-end fashions scrambling to re-invent their brands, in part by catering to younger shoppers who more often consider their impact on the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  than do traditional luxury-goods buyers.\par \par \uc2 In a recent survey, the Luxury Institute, a New York research firm, found that younger and more-affluent consumers seek information about \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  more actively than their older and less well-off counterparts. "Young consumers believe that caring about the \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  is how you create a meaningful life," said Milton Pedraza, the firm's CEO.\par \par \uc2 Some luxury companies jumped on the green bandwagon earlier than others. In 2004, PPR rival \uc2 LVMH\uc2 's \uc2 Louis Vuitton\uc2  brand conducted a "carbon inventory," to gauge its impact on greenhouse-gas emissions. Afterward, it cut back on corporate travel and air shipment of goods.\par \par \uc2 In 2007, PPR created a social and environmental responsibility department that reports directly to Mr. Pinault. PPR now ties part of executives' bonuses to achieving targets in seven areas -- from reducing carbon emissions to promoting diversity, Mr. Pinault said.\par \par \uc2 Later in 2007, a study by WWF, the wildlife conservation group, singled out the luxury-goods business as out of touch with eco-conscious trends. WWF ranked the top 10 luxury brands on their environmental and social track records; the highest "grade" was a C+, given to \uc2 L'Oreal SA\uc2 , Hermes and \uc2 LVMH\uc2 . (PPR got a "D.")\par \par \uc2 "Initially [the companies] were quite defensive," says Anthony Kleanthous, senior policy adviser for WWF and co-author of the study. But now they are pushing environmental and socially responsibility "as a positive driver of brand value," he said.\par \par \uc2 Laurent Claquin\uc2 , PPR's senior vice president of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , said the company's plans to develop a separate social-responsibility division were in the works well before the WWF report came out.\par \par \uc2 Around the same time, \uc2 LVMH\uc2 's \uc2 Louis Vuitton\uc2  leather-goods brand launched a "Core Values" ad campaign that has featured tennis player Andre Agassi, rocker Keith Richards and, most recently, astronaut Buzz Aldrin. The ads have emphasized the company's support for the Climate Project, and the celebrities appearing in them have donated at least part of their modeling fees to the nonprofit group, which was founded by Al Gore.\par \par \uc2 Last month, upscale retailer Barneys New York began promoting a collection of $75 sneakers with uppers and linings made of organic material. The sneakers were designed by organic-clothing brand Loomstate in a partnership with Keds.\par \par \uc2 This fall, luxury menswear label \uc2 Ermenegildo Zegna\uc2  will begin selling an "Ecotech Solar" jacket under its Zegna Sport label, with solar panels on its sleeves that can be used to recharge a battery and heat up the jacket's collar.\par \par \uc2 Whether the new tack will work remains to be seen. Increasingly, consumers and nonprofit groups are scrutinizing the validity of corporate environmental and social responsibility efforts.\par \par \uc2 For corporate alliances with nonprofit groups to succeed, companies need to disclose how much money they are donating or risk allegations of "greenwashing" -- or paying lip service to environmental causes to promote their products, says Mike Lawrence, an executive vice president at Cone LLC, a Boston-based marketing agency. "Puffery, unfortunately, is legal in advertising," he adds.\par \par \uc2 The global recession is adding challenges that defy simple solutions. Global sales of luxury goods are expected to fall 10% this year to 154 billion euros ($218 billion), the first decline in 15 years, according to \uc2 Bain &Co\uc2 . The industry isn't expected to return to 2008 levels, 170 billion euros, until 2012, says Claudia D'Arpizio, a consultant at Bain's Milan office. In response brands are slowing store expansion, lowering prices and trimming ad spending to cut costs.\par \par \uc2 Still, the economy may also accelerate the greening of luxury, industry executives say. A February survey by Cone found that 50% of Americans ages 18 to 24 said they have "higher expectations of companies to make and sell environmentally responsible products and services during the economic downturn," compared with 35% of Americans overall.\par \par {\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw183\pich406\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2745\pichgoal6090
