justright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 One of the parts of the European School of Management and Technology's MBA programme I was looking forward to the most was the "fieldtrip" - experiencing the multi-faceted perspective of doing business in an international context. The principal objective of the trip is for the students to explore a country that is expected to play a key role in future global business. This year we had a choice (perhaps not so surprisingly) between China and India.\par \par \uc2 As I had been to India before, I was particularly keen to revisit the country that is developing into an economic superpower.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 We had been given the chance to organise the programme ourselves and so could decide which companies to visit. The project was supervised by one of our marketing professors. An Indian, he proved to be an invaluable guide during the trip, not so much in showing us around, but in giving us the social, political and economic context of, for example, the caste system, the role of religion in Indian society and the impact of corruption on every day life.\par \par \uc2 During our 12-day stay, we visited a number of cities. Our first stop was Mumbai, the financial capital of the country, also dubbed "the Paris of India". Out of all the cities we visited, Mumbai lived up to its reputation, providing the sharpest contrast between rich and poor. All the multinationals, banks, insurers and consultants are present but suffocating poverty around every corner somehow prevents the city from developing a truly glowing financial centre.\par \par \uc2 After Mumbai we visited Pune. India's eighth largest city is well known for it's automotive industry and a visit to \uc2 Tata Motors\uc2  proved irresistible. We decided to do the 180 km trip journey by bus. It took us 5 hours and we witnessed at first hand how India's road infrastructure continues to be one of it's main challenges.\par \par \uc2 Tata Motors\uc2 , still lead by the legendary industrialist \uc2 Ratan Tata\uc2 , is renowned for it's \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The company was, for example, the first in India to let employees share in the company's profits. Tata has built it's own hospitals and schools, open to Tata employees and their extended families. In a country where public services cannot be taken for granted, companies sometimes appear to assume the role of local government.\par \par \uc2 Of course we also had to see the infamous Tata Nano, the cheap transportation alternative. We were told that the car will not be available in Europe or in the US for the foreseeable future as Tata focuses on Asia and Africa. "Where the people need a car like this the most", explained the company's spokesperson. It provided us with a good example of a company targeting the bottom of the pyramid.\par \par \uc2 Another topic we wanted to somehow address during our trip was India's energy problem. India's energy supply is said to be scarce, expensive and unreliable. Power cuts are so frequent that most of the companies have their own generator. One mobile phone company even integrated a flashlight in its newest model. Suzlon, a wind power company is trying to fill the gap left by the imperfections in India's energy supply by producing renewable energy.\par \par \uc2 But India does not seem to be ready for renewable energy sources, as today alternative energy companies still only marginally contribute to the ever-increasing energy needs of the world's fifth largest energy consumer. India's growing energy requirement is also likely to have a serious adverse effect on its \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 From there we travelled to Bangalore. It was as if we had arrived in a different country. The city was full of energy, innovation, creativity and newly gained prosperity. Although it was obvious that the financial crisis had struck in Bangalore, still India's "silicon valley" appeared to be in good shape - although most companies were reluctant to talk about their financial results. Besides giants such as SAP and Infosys, we visited a little IT-gem called MindTree.\par \par \uc2 Ten IT veterans, who still work at the company, founded this consultancy 10 years ago. We were struck by its approach towards \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 . As well as running a number of facilities for its employees, the company works closely with an organisation for disabled children. Besides donating funds, MindTree employs some of the children and one of them designed the company's logo. An inspiring example of where charity becomes an integrated part of the business model.\par \par \uc2 We concluded our trip in Delhi where we visited the United Nations Development Programme. It provided us with some hard facts and data and gave some perspective to our findings.\par \par \uc2 We knew for example that 64 per cent of the population is considered to be illiterate. However, we were unaware that people are deemed to be literate if they can write their name. We also discovered that although India is known for its good schools and universities, producing approximately 1 million engineers per year, due to the differences in the quality of education across the country only 20 per cent of those engineers are employable.\par \par \uc2 Back at school in Berlin, after sharing our findings with the faculty and those students who had visited China, we had a few weeks holiday. For many of us this "holiday" was also the start of our quest to find a job.\par \par \uc2 We have learned that not everyone from the class of 2008 has found a job yet, which illustrates what we already knew: jobs remain scarce and its a daunting task facing us. However, all the students remain positive and upbeat about the future.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 20090825_21985_11.xml\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 gdip : \uc2 International Relations | gedu : \uc2 Education | gcat : \uc2 Political/General News | gpir : \uc2 Politics/International Relations\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \c