s\par \par \uc2 Sovereign wealth fund worth $400bn\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Norway's $400bn sovereign wealth fund, the world's second-largest, is stepping up its efforts to monitor its investments in emerging markets for ethical, environmental and human rights infringements.\par \par \uc2 SourceAsia and CSR China, based in Oxford, will start reporting from November on the ethical performance of 2,300 companies in Asia invested in by the Norwegian Government Pension Fund, Paul Wenman, the research companies' managing director, told the Financial Times.\par \par \uc2 The initiative signals an attempt by Norway to expose its emerging market investments to the same level of ethical scrutiny faced by western companies in its portfolio, as the Nordic country tries to use its oil wealth to encourage \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The fund, which invests Norway's oil revenues for future generations, is often held up as a better governance model for opaque financial institutions, such as \uc2 Temasek\uc2  or the \uc2 Abu Dhabi Investment Authority\uc2 , that are rarely open about their investment strategies.\par \par \uc2 Norway has disinvested from numerous western companies, including \uc2 Wal-Mart\uc2 , the US retailer, and \uc2 Rio Tinto\uc2 , the Anglo-Australian mining group, over alleged ethical violations but taken few such steps against companies in the developing world.\par \par \uc2 Norway's move reflects growing investor concern surrounding labour standards, corruption and environmental damage in emerging markets.\par \par \uc2 But Mr Wenman said that finding information about companies in Asia's fast growing economies was often far more difficult than their counterparts in US and Europe, which are bound by stricter disclosure rules.\par \par \uc2 "From an investor's point of view, corruption and ethics [problems], which are endemic in the [Asian] region and hard to track down, are the hardest to manage," said Mr Wenman. "\b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  is the least to worry about [because the damage becomes apparent]".\par \par \uc2 About 10 per cent of Norway's so-called "oil fund" is invested in emerging markets after recent moves to reduce its dependence on European and US assets.\par \par \uc2 The Council on Ethics, which makes recommendations to the fund, said the number of companies included in the portfolio had increased from 2,500 to 8,000 over the past few years, many of them in non-English-speaking countries where ethical violations were harder to monitor.\par \par \uc2 The fund awarded a contract in July to Ecofact, a Zurich-based consultancy, to monitor its global investments but decided it needed specialised help to assess companies in China and some other Asian countries.\par \par \uc2 Under a four-year contract, SourceAsia and CSR China will provide the sovereign wealth fund's Council on Ethics with a confidential monthly report on alleged violations.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b RF\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 ftnewspaper_20090924.xml|2009092