ow} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 In the few instances in which co-operative banks have resorted to facilities, as mentioned in "Mutual suspicion" (September 2), they have done so with the intention of sustaining a rate of growth in their lending tailored to a degraded and risky \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Local co-operative banks were not hit directly by the financial crisis and they continue to provide credit to SMEs and contribute to the sustainability of local workforces.\par \par \uc2 Involvement of their members, according to the co-operative principle "one person-one vote", leads to a conservative risk management and to enhanced trust between the local co-operative bank and its members/customers.\par \par \uc2 The co-operative banking business model has shown its resilience during the peak of the financial crisis. Moreover, co-operative banks are very often the leaders in drawing up environmental strategies and giving real meaning to \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Focusing their business on long-term prosperity rather than short-term gains, basing their governance on democratic rules, and functioning in a decentralised system, they can pave the way for restoring confidence in banking.\par \par \uc2 Piet Moerland,\par \par \uc2 European Association of Co-operative Banks,\par \par \uc2 Brussels, Belgium\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx936