n0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (c) 2009 Dow Jones & Company, Inc. To see the edition in which this article appeared, click here \uc2 http://awsj.com.hk/factiva-ns\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Determined to retain your most talented executives? Well, here's some counterintuitive advice: The best way to keep them from leaving is to prepare them to do just that.\par \par \uc2 In tough economic times like these, retention becomes less of a priority for many companies as they focus on more-immediate business concerns. But companies that neglect this issue during a downturn may be in for a nasty surprise just as things start looking up: Historically, there is a significant increase in the number of executives leaving their companies as market conditions improve and more job opportunities open up.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 That's why it's crucial that companies get serious about retention now. And that means giving executives opportunities to take on greater responsibility, broaden their skills and cultivate a network of relationships with their peers.\par \par \uc2 Of course, executives want these opportunities largely because the skills, experience and relationships they acquire make them more valuable on the job market. So there is always the risk that a company may invest in building its executives' talents only to see some of them take those talents elsewhere.\par \par \uc2 But our research shows that executives intend to stay longest with companies that offer the greatest opportunities to enhance their employability. On balance, a company will keep more talent by helping its executives grow than it would by denying them these opportunities.\par \par \uc2 Too few companies understand this. We found wide discrepancies between what executives want in the way of professional development and what their companies are giving them. With that in mind, here's a look at how companies can address that gap by providing the three types of opportunities executives want most.\par \par \uc2 New Responsibilities\par \par \uc2 The executives we surveyed ranked opportunities to work on challenging tasks and to take on more responsibility higher than any other factor in career satisfaction. Providing these opportunities not only helps a company retain executives, but also helps the company identify and cultivate its next generation of leaders. That is especially true in times of adversity, like an economic downturn or a business turnaround, when executives have more opportunity to make their mark than they would when the business is thriving.\par \par \uc2 United Parcel Service Inc\uc2 . continually creates opportunities for employees to take on more challenging tasks and greater responsibilities. John Saunders, the company's vice president for human resources, says: "We don't view it as, 'We hired you to do this particular job.' We view it as, 'This is going to be a 30-year process.'"\par \par \uc2 UPS holds formal reviews with employees to discuss training opportunities, special assignments to work on solving particular problems, and other growth options. They discuss "things like what kind of assignments they need to round them out in preparation for the next promotion," says Peggy Gardner, director of customer communications. "We talk about their skills, their career objectives and what they want to do next," she says. "We figure out what we can do to help them achieve their goals."\par \par \uc2 Broader Skills\par \par \uc2 In addition to developing their leadership talents, executives want to increase their value by acquiring knowledge of operations outside their areas of expertise, and by polishing general business skills.\par \par \uc2 Consider the example of hotel giant \uc2 Marriott International Inc\uc2 . In an industry notorious for its high turnover rate, Marriott is exceptionally skilled at retaining managerial talent. One reason is a program that exposes talented managers to business issues and situations that prepare them to pursue promotions to general management roles.\par \par \uc2 For example, a marketing executive with little experience in hotel operations completed a training assignment in the operations division. To help her get up to speed quickly, she was assigned both senior and peer mentors. Moreover, she wasn't the only one who benefited from the experience. During her assignment, she shared some of her marketing knowledge with her colleagues in operations, by suggesting ways to attract more customers, for example.\par \par \uc2 Cultivating Relationships\par \par \uc2 Networking can help a company, not just by improving retention but also by increasing understanding and collaboration among various business units.\par \par \uc2 Consider the investment bank profiled in the book "Driving Results Through Social Networks," written by Rob Cross and Robert J. Thomas. The authors found that the social networks of the bank's senior vice presidents were different from those of its junior vice presidents.\par \par \uc2 The bank held several events so that these individuals could connect and forge more-productive personal networks. After a year, the retention rate of this group was much higher than that for the investment bank as a whole.\par \par \uc2 ---\par \par \uc2 Dr. Craig is research fellow at the \uc2 Accenture\uc2  Institute for High Performance in Boston. Dr. Kimberly is a professor of management at the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School. Mr. Cheese was until recently the managing director of \uc2 Accenture\uc2 's Talent and Organization Performance consulting practice world-wide. They can be reached at reports@wsj.com.\par \par \uc2 ---\par \par \uc2 For Further Reading\par \par \uc2 These related articles from MIT Sloan Management Review can be accessed online at sloanreview.mit.edu/wsj\par \par \uc2 Strategies for Preventing a Knowledge-Loss Crisis\par \par \uc2 By Salvatore Parise, Rob Cross and Thomas H. Davenport (Summer 2006)\par \par \uc2 Departing employees leave with more than what they know; they also take with them critical knowledge about who they know. That information needs to be a part of any knowledge-retention strategy.\par \par \uc2 Using \b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate Social Responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  to Win the War for Talent\par \par \uc2 By C.B. Bhattacharya, Sankar Sen and Daniel Korschun (Winter 2008)\par \par \uc2 New research indicates there are five steps that can help business leaders increase the effectiveness of \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a lever for talent management.\par \par \uc2 Making People Decisions in the New Global \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\par \par \uc2 By Claudio Fernandez-Araoz (Fall 2007)\par \par \uc2 Finding the right individuals to fill executive positions has never been easy, and the process is only getting more difficult with increased globalization.\par \par \uc2 How to Retain Talent in India\par \par \uc2 By Elaine Appleton Grant (Fall 2008)\par \par \uc2 Providing support, training and opportunities from day one is critical.\par \par \uc2 When 'Stars' Migrate, Do They Still Perform Like Stars?\par \par \uc2 By Boris Groysberg, Lex Sant and Robin Abrahams (Fall 2008)\par \par \uc2 As research on the National Football League reveals, sometimes the specific nature of a job determines whether a great performer at one company can replicate that performance at another.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.djreprints.com/link/DJRFactiva.html?FACTIVA=waco20091025000013"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 License this article from Dow Jones Reprint Service}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b NS\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 c42 : \uc2 Labor/Personnel Issues | nnam : \uc2 News Agency Material | ccat : \uc2 Corporate/Industrial News | ncat : \uc2 Content Types | nfact : \uc2 Factiva Filters | nfce : \uc2 FC&E Exclusion Filter | nfcpin : \uc2 FC&E Industry News Filter | niwe : \uc2 IWE Filter\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clp