faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Salaries in the sector are gradually becoming more attractive, says Rebecca Knight\par \par \uc2 Until recently, the only reason managers launched environmental campaigns was to promote their company's reputation. But today, with the high cost of energy, water scarcity and diminishing access to raw materials, sustainability is increasingly at the top of organisations' agendas\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 As a result, business schools around the world are sharpening their focus on the issue. Many schools are infusing environmental concerns throughout their curriculums and introducing classes and concentrations in social responsibility.\par \par \uc2 According to the Aspen Institute Center for Business Education , a group that measures how well schools are preparing students for the environmental, social and ethical complexities of the business world, the percentage of schools that require students to take a course dedicated to business and society issues has increased dramatically over time: from 34 per cent in 2001 to 69 per cent in 2009.\par \par \uc2 "In the past, a lot of efforts to help save the planet have come from government and nongovernmental organisations," says Brad Gentry, senior lecturer in sustainable investments at the Yale School of Management and co-director of the Center for Business and the \b \highlight22\uc2 Environment\b0 \highlight\uc2  at the university. "But increasingly, business is playing an important part of those efforts, through innovative technologies, enhanced products and improved management techniques.\par \par \uc2 "We know you can get filthy rich destroying the planet, but now we're starting to think about how you can make lots of money saving the planet."\par \par \uc2 He says that the focus on sustainability in MBA programmes is not a passing fad; rather, schools are trying to change the way aspiring managers measure the bottom line and identify where to maximise profits and environmental and social performance.\par \par \uc2 Corporate engagement with business schools on sustainability issues is critical to the success of these programmes, according to business school officials. A cynic might question how deeply companies believe in the value of social responsibility but Tom Lyon, director of the Erb Institute at University of Michigan who holds an endowed chair at the school from \uc2 Dow Chemical\uc2 , insists that companies that approach him are "sincere".\par \par \uc2 "I am sure there's some degree of reputation and image building, but there is also a sincere effort to be connected with a university. These companies want to be up to speed on the latest thinking, to know what students are thinking and to understand how to get the next generation's best and brightest to come work for them."\par \par \uc2 Many schools say they have launched specialised degrees and concentrations in sustainability due to student demand but there remains the challenge of persuading business students that there are viable - and lucrative - career opportunities in the field.\par \par \uc2 Prof Lyons says salaries in sustainability and \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  are rising. "The reason is that investment banks are hiring people who know about renewable energy and consulting firms are building new practices on climate and sustainability."\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\c