Dow Jones & Company, Inc. To see the edition in which this article appeared, click here \uc2 http://awsj.com.hk/factiva-ns\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 India's Corporate Affairs Minister Salman Khurshid is New Delhi's man in charge of regulating the country's vibrant companies.\par \par \uc2 He took the position in May in the wake of the \uc2 Satyam Computer Services Ltd\uc2 .'s book-cooking scandal with the aim of promoting better corporate governance and ethics. Soon he hopes to see the Companies Bill become law. The bill replaces a 1956 law on how companies are run and revamps regulations on everything from mergers and acquisitions to insider trading to class-action suits.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Encouraging \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  is another important job of the minister. Mr. Khurshid has been in the news lately for suggesting India could have an exchange for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  credits along the lines of carbon credits. He said the government might even extend tax incentives to companies for their non-business services to society in areas like helping with education, health and \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The 56-year old Mr. Khurshid said in an interview with The Wall Street Journal's Krishna Pokharel that he aims to bridge the gap between "corporate India and the rest of India."\par \par \uc2 Edited excerpts:\par \par \uc2 WSJ: You have been encouraging inclusive growth and social responsibility in the corporate sector. What is the ministry doing to help companies work toward these goals?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Khurshid: \b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  has to come both from within and from without. From within because it has to become part of corporate culture, especially in our country where we need growth with equity, growth which is inclusive and growth that lifts everyone together.\par \par \uc2 From the outside, we can create special incentives: fiscal advantage, special opportunities, benefits, state support and market support. I think a new generation of incentives could be provided for the right kind of growth, growth which is inclusive, growth which is responsible.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: What role do you envision for the corporate sector in India which is largely poor and rural?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Khurshid: Today, we have a huge number of people involved in agriculture but there is very little corporate involvement in the sector. Some 18% of our GDP comes from the agriculture sector whereas it involves 80% of our population. Obviously, that needs to be corrected. Our GDP from agriculture has to grow. Value addition in agriculture has to grow. If that is to happen -- with better remuneration for agriculturalists without backbreaking costs to consumers -- then we need to involve the corporate sector.\par \par \uc2 How that can be done is again a very big challenge. We have the cooperative sector, which is in sugar, for instance, doing a massively important job in states like Maharashtra and so on. But can we extend that to other areas as well, other states and other sectors, other than sugar cane? Then we should think of what kind of interface we can provide between the small Indian farmer and the corporate sector. I think this is the big challenge and the big question.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: How would you define the ideal Indian corporation?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Khurshid: Well, there are lots of models available. I think it would be unfair for me to say which is the right one. Periodically, among themselves, companies recognize leaders. Certainly, through business organizations there is a periodic interface between us and them. We asked Mr. J.J. Irani [director of \uc2 Tata Sons Ltd\uc2 .] to head the committee on reform of the Companies Law that wrote the report that became the basis of the legislation that is now before Parliament so you can see where our recognition lies.\par \par \uc2 Gradually, systems will develop by which we can start selecting role models. I can tell you that we are impressed when someone like \uc2 ITC Ltd\uc2 . sets up triple bottom line institutions. When somebody commits to Millennium Development Goals, when somebody commits to the best practices in CSR, when somebody goes out and does something which is directly leading to a better profile as far as climate change is concerned, these would be very significant things.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: Do you think India needs legislation on business ethics?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Khurshid: Whether we need to have legislation or not, it's too early to say. We are now talking about greater disclosure, greater participation of shareholders, better structures, higher responsibility, awareness about your responsibility, etc. This is what the Companies Bill will do but the bill is not the last step. There will be other steps to be taken, but let's take the first step.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: Does the ministry keep track of how much companies are investing in \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 ?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Khurshid: Yes, but only roughly. There have to be compulsory disclosures. If there are compulsory disclosures in your balance sheets and in your annual reports then all this will be easy to monitor. Right now you have to ask, or a company must feel proud of what it has done before it discloses. There are no separate CSR disclosures yet required as far as the law is concerned.\par \par \uc2 People might want to put it in their annual reports. But there is today no automatic monitoring process of this. When I talk about carbon credits and similar \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  credits, it means you will have to create institutions and structures to be able to do that. We will have to give it substance, we will have to make it measurable, we will have to make it deliverable and we will have to make it exchangeable. All these things we will have to discuss. It's too early to say that's exactly what it will be. A CSR exchange is a new idea. I see no reason why India should always follow what others have done. We want to create something which others must follow.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: How do you think the Satyam fiasco changed the corporate culture in India?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Khurshid: It was a wake-up call on certain issues but I don't think that we were in such a deep sleep that we didn't know what could go wrong. The Companies Bill already provides for many things that we have discovered from Satyam crisis. But chronologically, the bill was drafted but not enacted. If it had been enacted at that time, then we might have prevented Satyam.\par \par \uc2 WSJ: By when will the new Companies Bill be enacted?\par \par \uc2 Mr. Khurshid: Hopefully in the coming year.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.djreprints.com/link/DJRFactiva.html?FACTIVA=waco20091216000017"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 License this article from Dow Jones Reprint Service}}}