\li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SN\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 The Wall Street Journal Europe\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b SC\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 WSJE\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b PG\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 R6\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LA\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 English\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CY\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 (Copyright (c) 2010, Dow Jones & Company, Inc.) \par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b LP\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 When the going gets tough, costly good intentions can go out the window. Company spending has been squeezed by the global recession and budgets for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  have suffered disproportionately.\par \par \uc2 A survey of U.K. businesses by KPMG and Business In The Community found a third of companies cut their \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  budgets in 2009. Corporate philanthropy has also been hit, with a study by the Giving USA Foundation revealing that charitable donations by U.S. companies fell by 8% in inflation-adjusted terms in 2008.\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b TD\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Perhaps this is not so great a loss. There is a growing feeling among company executives that marginal initiatives, which can so easily be dispensed, are not enough to alter corporate behavior. In a speech last year, \uc2 Stephen Green\uc2 , chairman of U.K. bank \uc2 HSBC\uc2 , said: "There has been a tendency to compartmentalize so-called \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities as an adjunct to the mainstream business activities." Mr. Green believes in replacing \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  with a new focus on "corporate sustainability," which, rather than being an add-on to a business. "is about the raison d'etre of the company itself."\par \par \uc2 Many of the senior executives at Davos this year talked about the social responsibilities of business as opposed to their fundamental business responsibilities. Speaking during a session at the World Economic Forum, \uc2 Eric Schmidt\uc2 , chief executive of \uc2 Google\uc2 , said he sees no difference between the two. \uc2 Google\uc2  is into innovation, he said, and "innovation is fundamentally about how the world can become a better place."\par \par \uc2 David Bent, head of business strategies at Forum for the Future, which is a nongovernment organization that advises businesses on ethical business strategies, says the use of the term \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  is declining. The focus has now shifted to sustainable business. He says: "\b \highlight22\uc2 Corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  asked the question: what is the impact of this business on the world? Sustainable business asks the question: what is the impact of the world on this business?"\par \par \uc2 This shift in thinking began before the credit crisis struck, but is now gaining momentum. Scott Beaudoin, director of cause marketing at MS&L in Boston, says: "Companies are asking how they can be socially responsible in a way that also moves the business forward. It's no longer about having one \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  guy who is supposed to be the moral compass for the company, like a chaplain in an Army regiment. It's about making sustainable business the standard operating procedure."\par \par \uc2 Sustainable business, Mr. Bent says, looks at how a business can adapt to global social and environmental trends, such as future regulation on carbon output, water shortages, and changing demographics. He adds: "It looks at a company's survival and future success in a world of limited resources."\par \par \uc2 Such initiatives suffered a serious setback last year, with the failure of governments to agree on a post-Kyoto legal framework to cope with climate change at Copenhagen.\par \par \uc2 Leo Johnson, partner for sustainability and climate change at \uc2 PricewaterhouseCoopers\uc2 , says: "Sustainable business has faced the ultimate double whammy of the credit crunch and the total damp squib that was Copenhagen. If climate change was the great driver for \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2 , then that driver seems to have stalled."\par \par \uc2 However, in this area at least, the business world appears to be pulling ahead of governments and public opinion in pushing for greater action on climate change.\par \par \uc2 Leo Apotheker, chief executive of the software company SAP, wrote last month: "Many large companies are already taking matters into their own hands. The hope, of course, is that politicians will take note and respond with a global regulatory framework, but business leaders know they cannot wait for this framework before acting."\par \par \uc2 Companies are acting to reduce their carbon footprint, make the carbon cost of their goods more transparent, and also to encourage governments to reach a new climate-change treaty. Much of this goes beyond altruism. An international legal framework will bring some much needed certainty to their future operating \b \highlight22\uc2 environment\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Becoming less energy-intensive and more sustainable saves companies money and earns loyalty from customers and employees.\par \par \uc2 One example is \uc2 Marks &Spencer\uc2 , the U.K. retailer, which initially lagged peers on sustainability initiatives, but then very publicly launched its own initiative, Plan A, in 2007, promising to invest GBP 200 million ($323 million) over five years to make the company greener.\par \par \uc2 By 2009, the company said energy and waste cost savings had already made the initiative cash positive, and also made it the most reputable U.K. brand in the eyes of consumers, according to research conducted by the Reputation Institute.\par \par \uc2 Such initiatives also increase employee loyalty. \uc2 Coca-Cola Enterprises\uc2  conducted a survey of its 60,000 staff and found that \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  was the second biggest driver of staff engagement, after leadership.\par \par \uc2 Several companies have tried to tap into this by offering employees the ability to take paid days off to volunteer for social projects. Mike Kelly, head of corporate sustainability at KPMG, says: "Companies are trying to use all their resources effectively, including freeing up staff to volunteer."\par \par \uc2 Having a strong values-driven strategy is important for winning customer loyalty too, in an age when customers are grumpy, cynical, and increasingly well-organized through social networking sites like \uc2 Facebook\uc2  and Twitter.\par \par \uc2 A survey of 130,000 \uc2 Facebook\uc2  users conducted by Georgetown University and the World Economic Forum found that only a quarter of respondents believed corporations have a "values-driven" approach to business.\par \par \uc2 Last year, there were several examples of Twitter campaigns against companies. In April one was launched against Amazon.com, the online retailer, for suppressing the sales ranking of books deemed to contain gay, lesbian or bisexual subject matter. The move, which appears to have been a cataloguing mistake, prompted a Twitter storm that made newspaper headlines within a few hours.\par \par \uc2 But although the demands of employees, customers and the strain of diminishing natural resources make a strong case for more sustainable and values-driven business models, the most important driver will be governments introducing new national and international regulations on carbon emissions, water usage and even, potentially, food consumption.\par \par \uc2 Mr. Johnson of \uc2 PricewaterhouseCoopers\uc2  says: "If governments provide a strong legal framework that aligns incentives with business, then you have something you could call sustainability. If not, then \b \highlight22\uc2 corporate social responsibility\b0 \highlight\uc2  will just be glace cherries on an unsustainable cake."\par \par \uc2 ---\par \par \uc2 Mr. Evans is a writer based in London. He can be reached at reports@wsj.com.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://www.djreprints.com/link/DJRFactiva.html?FACTIVA=weco20100203000008"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 License this article from Dow Jones Reprint Service}}}\par \cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\row} \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx720\clvertalt\clpadl15\clpadr-15 \cellx9360\pard \qr \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \b CO\b0\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 mks : \uc2 Marks & Spencer Group PLC\cell \pard